<TEXT>
energy secretary james watkins said wednesday 
a nuclear weapons plant in the pacific northwest released enough 
radiation in the 1940s to pose a serious health hazard to nearby 
residents 
it was the first time the government has acknowledged that 
radiation emissions from the hanford nuclear reservation were high 
enough to cause illnesses incluuding cancer in people living 
nearby 
watkins speaking in advance of a study on the richland wash 
plant to be released thursday said the implications of the 
report are serious 
watkins said the report is expected to contain estimates of 
potentially large doses of radiation from the hanford plant from 
1944 to 1947 
when i say high i mean significantly high 3000 rads 
thousands of rads he said 
a rad is a measure of radiation exposure to human tissue the 
nuclear regulatory commission requires that facilities it licenses 
limit yearly radiation exposure from airborne emissions to 15 
thousandths of a rad 
he said between 350000 and 400000 curies of radioactive 
material was released in one episode in 1945 a curie is the amount 
of radiation emitted in one second by 1400 pounds of enriched 
uranium 
the study being released thursday is the first part of a 
fiveyear 15 million study that is the first major research into 
accidental and intentional release of massive amounts of radiation 
that drifted from hanford into ten nearby washington and oregon 
counties 
the report will cover emissions but not the health effects of 
the radiation said angela beers spokeswoman for the panel of 18 
nongovernment scientists and experts that directed the review 
but a parallel study under way at the centers for disease 
control will use the exposure estimates to try to document cases of 
thyroid disease among hanford area residents she said 
watkins said at his press conference that the main source of 
worrisome exposure was radioiodine the same isotope that caused 
radiation sickness in some residents who lived near the soviet 
unions nuclear power plant at chernobyl when radiation was 
released in a 1986 accident 
a number of people who lived across the columbia river from 
hanfords nine reactors claimed the 1940s emissions caused cancer 
and thyroidrelated illnesses 
i dont want you to think we do this today watkins said 
we are not casual about this today but we do have to go back and 
look at what happened to people we dont know who was at the right 
spot at the wrong time we have to learn lessons out of this and 
be sensitive to the human beings who were there at the time 
the hanford environmental dose reconstruction project uses 
computer models to estimate how much radiation escaped when 
plutonium was produced at the 560squaremile nuclear plant 
scientists will use the firstphase estimates to test and refine 
computer models over the next two years during the second phase 
said john till a south carolina nuclear scientist and the panels 
chairman 
radioactive iodine was produced when spent reactor fuel rods 
were chemicall dissolved to produce weaponsgrade plutonium and 
uranium when it concentrates in the thyroid gland iodine131 can 
cause cancer and other diseases 
judith jurji president of the hanford downwinders coalition 
said she and five members of her family have hypothyroidism which 
causes sluggishness and puffiness her father and two uncles worked 
at hanford from 1949 to 1956 
however it would be very difficult to prove a longterm illness 
was caused by exposure more than 40 years ago and law prohibits 
lawsuits against the government said jim thomas of the 
spokanebased hanford education action league 
researchers studied air emissions from 1944 to 1947 and 
contaminated cooling water emissions into the columbia river from 
1964 to 1967 in part because those were years of highest radiation 
releases and the best documented ms beers said 
weaponsgrade plutonium was produced at the plant from 1943 
until 1988 but radiation emissions steadily decreased over the 
last 30 years 
the energy department is paying for the study but has no 
supervisory authority 
</TEXT>
