<TEXT>
dressed in expensive gold jewelry and designer 
casual wear a man being arraigned on drug possession charges says 
he made up to 90000 over three years in washingtons illegal 
narcotics trade 
i can go out here stand on a corner and wait for business to 
come to me you know the man who identified himself only as 
archie a 21yearold district of columbia resident said tuesday 
i work for somebody but i dont have anybody standing over 
me i just have to give the people what they want take their 
money make sure it gets back to where it belongs and get my cut 
he said 
archie said he made between 75000 to 90000 over three 
years 
the lure of making large sums of money in a short period of time 
is the main reason why many poor black urban males in the nations 
capital participate in the underground drug trade according to a 
study released by the rand corp on tuesday 
the report was based on information gathered among 186 
washington dc men aged 1840 who said they had been involved in 
drug activity and were on probation it said the average 
streetlevel operative is a poor urban black male who makes a 
median income of 24000 annually from narcotics sales 
archie who is black and who lives in a poorer section of 
washington fits the statistical profile he said he viewed the 
charges facing him in dc superior court as part of the cost of 
plying his illegal trade 
i dont have no supervisor i dont have no overhead and i 
dont have no hassles the only thing i got to worry about is being 
picked up by the law he said 
this is my fifth arrest but ive never been convicted and 
this just interrupts what i do 
archies lawyer angela burns confirmed that her client had 
been arrested five times in the past three years on drug and 
weapons charges but had no convictions 
the rand report also used information supplied by the city 
government about the 24000 people arrested for selling or 
possessing drugs from 1985 through 1987 and a survey of 387 boys 
aged 15 to 18 
the report estimated that in 1987 an estimated 24000 district 
residents were selling drugs on the street for the three in eight 
who were dealing drugs every day the median monthly earnings were 
2000 or 30 an hour taxfree after expenses 
that compares with the 7 an hour from the legitimate jobs that 
75 percent of the probationers reported holding 
the study found that dealers active at least two days a week 
face a 22 percent chance of going to prison a 7 percent chance of 
severe injury and a 14 percent chance of being killed a fatality 
rate 100 times that of the general work force 
given those risks long periods of steady earnings are 
unlikely to be common the report said 
the estimated median income of streetlevel drug dealers was 
higher than the average 12898 earned by retail trade workers in 
198788 according to the city government 
construction workers made 24879 on average while service 
industry workers made 26545 the average annual salary for all 
private sector workers was 25857 while government employees made 
32118 
but those workers are subject to federal and local income tax 
withholding 
economist peter reuter the chief author of the rand study 
said the creation of considerably higher paying legitimate jobs 
probably wouldnt get us very far dealers would still have smaller 
total incomes than they can earn now by supplementing their regular 
wages with drug selling also many of them have expensive drug 
habits 
reuter said in an interview that while most streetlevel sales 
were by blacks the availability of drugs in washington affects not 
just the citys predominantly black population but white 
suburbanites as well 
while a typical city street dealers earnings arent enough to 
finance flashy cars and lavish lifestyles it is the image of such 
luxuries that draw many young men into selling drugs he said 
</TEXT>
