<TEXT>
its stadiums are shabby its fans remain rowdy and 
it still cant produce a tennis player good enough to get past the 
second round at wimbledon 
forget all that england was back on top of the sports heap 
tuesday at least from its own island vantage point 
fans could fill themselves with pride along with beer at the 
local pub as within 4 hours on a typically cloudy summer day two 
events restored the nation so long associated with the downside of 
sport to no 1 
first the european soccer federation voted to readmit english 
clubs into two of its three continental tournaments next year 
the clubs were banned in 1985 when 39 people died in a rampage 
by english fans through a belgian stadium 
we are back read the inchhigh headline on the evening 
standard londons afternoon newspaper 
sports minister colin moynihan hailed it as the dawning of a 
new era 
then just as the country was drinking in that dram of good news 
came a double shot england won a cricket series on home soil for 
the first time in five years 
bbctv interrupted its news headlines to announce the victory 
the excitement was understandable england gave the game to the 
world but in recent years the world has caught up and the last 
time the english won a homefield test series a string of major 
international matches each lasting five days was against 
australia in 1985 
they defeated sri lanka at home in 1988 but that was something 
like the oakland athletics beating the toledo mud hens 
tuesdays events heightened an already giddy feeling around 
english sports 
the national soccer team did much better than expected at the 
world cup reaching the semifinals before losing in a shootout to 
west germany the eventual champion prime minister margaret 
thatcher wants to have the players over for tea an invitation that 
would have been unthinkable just a month ago given the national 
humiliation brought upon her country by rowdy fans 
english racecar driver nigel mansell is a favorite at this 
weekends british grand prix formula 1 event and next week nick 
faldo of england probably the best golfer in the world has a 
chance to add the british open to his us masters titles from the 
last two years 
but all is not as rosy as an english garden 
soccer authorities still dont know how they will meet new 
stadium safety rules imposed after 95 deaths in a crush of fans at 
a game last year the government remains redfaced over the 
expulsion of more than 300 english soccer fans from italy after 
fights in sardinia rimini and turin 
and the tennis the land of fred perry and virginia wade failed 
to get a player into the third round of the mens or womens 
singles at wimbledon again this year and british bookies laid odds 
before the tournament of 1000to1 against a homegrown mens 
champion and 20001 against a womens winner 
the odds against an alien landing on earth this century are 
1001 
those bookies may hum god save the queen as they figure the 
hunches but they dont let the tune cloud their minds 
when the european soccer federation announced its decision on 
readmission william hill one of the countrys biggest bookmakers 
offered 71 against an english club winning a european trophy next 
season 
