<TEXT>
anthems played flags unfurled videotape rolled 
and then the leaders of the western world shook hands yet again 
if the small talk was running thin it didnt show 
president bush and several other summit leaders had been through 
all the pomp and ceremony less than a week ago that was at the 
nato gathering in london 
for the four european leaders here houston was the third time 
in three weeks that theyve lined up for group photographs 
attended state banquets and pondered weighty communiques 
britains margaret thatcher west germanys helmut kohl italys 
giulio andreotti and frances francois mitterrand began the long 
summer of summitry in the irish capital dublin with a european 
community summit at the end of june 
only japans toshiki kaifu added a fresh face in houston 
economic summits were once a highlight of the year a rare 
chance to hobnob with allied peers and walk the world stage 
but with the upheaval in eastern europe and accelerating moves 
toward closer unity among the west europeans summits have become 
almost routine 
during the bush administration there have already been two 
summits of the north atlantic treaty organization the european 
community holding regular emergency summits has virtually 
doubled its regular sixmonthly meetings 
the dynamics are changing but in the view of some analysts the 
lack of novelty doesnt diminish the significance 
i think summits are more important now said robert hormats 
a vice president of goldman sachs international who from 1975 to 
1982 was the us economic sherpa the aide who prepares the 
presidents agenda for summits 
during the cold war period security concerns bound us 
together in the west he said now these will no longer be as 
strong and you need something to bind and these will be economic 
issues if they are managed correctly 
hormats also sees summits as a discipline against insularity 
and for an economically less dominant united states an important 
forum for wielding influence through consensus 
it keeps them all constructively engaged in the global system 
because they know if they are not someone will raise the point 
when they next meet its a collective peer pressure exercise 
he said 
it has also become a lot less formal behind the closed doors 
according to aides to prime minister margaret thatcher 
she should know shes the western worlds longest serving 
leader and houston was her 12th economic summit 
in the beginning she routinely turned up at summits in combative 
moods and often became the center of a dispute particularly with 
her fellow europeans 
but over the years she has come to recognize the value of 
summits said an aide speaking on condition of anonymity the 
leaders do get to know each other and now its become easier it 
has also become a lot less predictable 
but what do they actually do apart from talk 
c fred bergsten director of the washingtonbased institute for 
international economics and a former senior us treasury official 
said that in the 1980s the economic summits drifted into general 
political issues and became a lot less actionoriented 
in my view they deteriorated enormously said bergsten 
i really hope and think theres a chance that this first one 
of the 90s will go back to make some headway on a few concrete 
issues he added citing farm subsidies free trade and soviet 
aid 
but hormats like many observers thinks the summits could use a 
lot fewer words ceremonials photo opportunities and the 
blowbyblow briefings that officials give to the hundreds of 
reporters who gather round 
it would be a lot better if they changed these laundrylist 
communiques covering every conceivable issue hormats said 
and in my view these summits will have come of age when there 
doesnt need to be so much hoopla 
bush spokesman marlin fitzwater said the leaders comfortable 
with one another hashed out most of the issues themselves rather 
than relying on aides 
the issues theyve dealt with in this summit have been real 
and dealt with by the heads at the table in a more direct way than 
any ive ever seen said fitzwater who has been to five economic 
summits 
for the summiteers theres no relief in sight 
the european community has already scheduled an extra meeting in 
october nato has invited president mikhail s gorbachev to speak 
perhaps this year and a really big summit a mass gathering of 
the 35 nations of east and west in the conference on security and 
cooperation in europe is expected before years end 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
maureen johnson of the aps london bureau 
covers british politics and is a veteran reporter of western 
summits 
</TEXT>
