<TEXT>
most cosmetic surgery to improve the 
appearance of military dependents retirees and their dependents 
will be halted at military hospitals under a new defense department 
policy 
but such procedures will not be totally barred for activeduty 
military personnel a pentagon spokeswoman said tuesday 
such operations will be conducted only on a very limited 
basis said spokeswoman susan hansen it will be done on the 
lowest priority and there must be no other requirement for the 
surgical theater at the time 
the pentagon reviewed its policy on procedures such as 
facelifts breast enlargements and liposuctions after receiving an 
inquiry from rep john murtha dpa chairman of the house 
appropriations defense subcommittee 
in april the san diego tribune reported that the san diego 
naval hospital one of four navy hospitals with an extensive 
plastic surgery department had performed 544 cosmetic procedures 
in the past two years and that air force and army hospitals 
performed similar cosmetic surgeries 
pentagon officials have argued that it is important for military 
surgeons to perform such procedures as part of their training 
but following a review of the legislative history of the policy 
defense department officials decided that a better 
interpretation of the legislation governing such procedures was 
needed ms hansen said 
consequently facelifts and other procedures relating to the 
aging process and any procedure performed for personal 
nontherapeutic reasons to improve the appearance will not be 
provided for activeduty dependents or retirees and their 
dependents using appropriated funds a pentagon statement said 
surgeries for the correction of a congenital abnormality 
reconstructive surgery following an injury or surgical or 
therapeutic trauma and postmastectomy breast reconstruction will 
be allowed the statement added 
ms hansen said the military services will develop procedures 
to assure that surgical residents and staff can meet the 
requirements of certification by their the medical specialty 
boards 
the new regulations are expected to be identical to those 
procedures covered under the civilian health and medical program 
for the uniformed services the insurance program known as champus 
that allows service members and their dependents to receive health 
care in private facilities ms hansen said 
champus doesnt cover purely cosmetic surgery 
</TEXT>
