taken down 
whether the army and police will back mrs chamorros new 
government or let the strike widen is considered crucial in the 
outcome of the walkouts now in their second week 
we mustnt repress the people one policeman said 
the sandinistas lost the presidential election to mrs chamorro 
on feb 25 ending 10 years of revolutionary rule of this country 
of 37 million residents the us economic embargo which helped 
create shortages even in basic foodstuffs contributed to their 
defeat 
mrs chamorro won with the backing of a 14party coalition that 
ranged from far right to communist and had little more in common 
than a distaste for the sandinistas 
the us trade sanctions and a long war against the 
ussupported contra rebels devastated the economy before mrs 
chamorro took office and her reconstruction efforts have stirred 
resentment and opposition 
sandinistaled unions called the strike to protest what they 
said were massive firings of government workers and to demand a 
voice in government economic policy which they say favors the 
wealthy under the new government 
labor leaders say 90000 people are taking part in the strike 
mrs chamorros government declared the action illegal last week 
claiming it was politically motivated 
gunfire spread from eastern managuas workingclass 
neighborhoods to the central section at the offices radio 
corporation the armed civilians who barricaded themselves there 
said they were protecting the station from sandinistas who wanted 
to burn it they said they tended up to 20 wounded in the radio 
station but there had been no deaths 
many prosandinista groups at the roadblocks carry sovietbloc 
ak47 assault rifles standard issue in the sandinista army 
thousands of ak47s were distributed to sandinista sympathizers 
after the february election defeat government demands for return 
of the weapons were largely ignored 
strikers have taken over most government ministries and many 
staterun enterprises the international airport is closed by an 
air controllers strike and water has been cut to parts of the city 
electrical service was restored tuesday but workers said they 
would start selective cuts around the city 
postal workers and telephone operators are on strike leaving 
the relatively few nicaraguans with directdial capacity the only 
ones who can communicate outside the country 
driving was difficult in some areas impossible in others 
because of barricades 
hundreds of factories and businesses shut down monday because 
employees could not get to work 
some walked to their jobs 
i will have to walk several kilometers to my job said marta 
gonzalez a household maid if i dont work i dont eat 
