<TEXT>
savings and loan bailout officials are 
shifting strategy and trying to save taxpayers money by closing 
troubled thrifts just before rather than after the institutions 
fail 
the board of the resolution trust corp voted 40 tuesday to 
adopt the accelerated resolutions program it will become the 
preferred course of action for handling failing thrifts rtc 
chairman l william seidman said 
officials estimate they could use the program for between 155 
and 180 of the 260 sampls expected to fail over the next year they 
plan to see how it works with 10 institutions over the summer 
previously the trust corporations tactic has been to seize an 
insolvent institution appoint a government managing agent to rein 
in any highflying practices and sell the sampl to whoever offers to 
accept the least amount of government aid 
the problem is that the last step was coming months sometimes 
more than a year after the initial seizure in the meantime 
longtime depositors and key employees were fleeing the institution 
reducing its value as an ongoing business 
under the new program the agency hopes it will be able to spend 
fewer taxpayer dollars by finding a buyer before an institution is 
stigmatized as failed the method is similar to how the federal 
deposit insurance corp handles commercial banks in trouble 
rather than publicly advertise for bids the rtc will solicit 
proposals for stillopen but weak sampls from a list of about 3500 
investors who have expressed an interest in acquiring failed 
institutions 
when a buyer is selected the institution will be closed and 
immediately reopened relieving the new owners of legal claims 
against the old institution 
the old shareholders will lose their investment the old 
managers will keep or lose their jobs depending on whether they 
played a part in causing the institution to fail 
generally if no buyer is found within 90 days the institution 
will be seized by the government 
this is a program designed to sell institutions in the most 
efficient and quickest manner possible with the least possible 
deterioration in value seidman said 
private analysts cautiously endorsed the strategy although they 
noted that the rtc has yet to deal with nearly 250 institutions 
that failed previously it has handled more than 200 failed thrifts 
in its first 11 months 
i think in principle its a good idea the only question is 
whether they are so overloaded now with all the clearly insolvent 
institutions said robert litan of the brookings institution a 
liberaloriented washington think tank 
youre going to be using scarce resources for marginally 
insolvent thrifts ahead of other institutions that are clearly in 
much worse shape he said 
however litan said taxpayers might save money by bailing out an 
institution on the edge of insolvency when its owners may be most 
tempted to gamble a deeply insolvent sampl under government control 
often is not in danger of further deterioration he said 
if youre in the government the thing to do is not to focus 
on past losses but to focus on how to prevent future losses from 
occurring he said 
auburn university economist james barth said the program might 
be a better way of handling the loans real estate and other assets 
of a failed thrift 
in the conventional sampl bailouts so far the government has been 
stuck with about half of the assets which it hopes to sell later 
officials hope that in accelerated resolution deals the new owner 
rather than the government will get most of the assets 
the rtc has so many assets it has to try new and different 
things to get those assets back into the private sector barth 
said if theyre not careful theyre going to wind up with the 
worlds largest troubled savings and loan and its going to be 
called the resolution trust corp 
</TEXT>
