<TEXT>
summit leaders struggled to break a deadlock in a 
useuropean fight over billions of dollars in farm subsidies with 
indications early wednesday morning that negotiators were closing 
in on a possible agreement 
officials close to the negotiations who spoke on conditition 
that they not be named said the language being discussed would 
provide for cuts in farm subsidies in each of the three areas 
singled out by the united states 
the language being considered would call for substantial 
progressive reductions in subsidies in the areas of export 
subsidies internal price supports and barriers to imports 
the united states had insisted that all three areas be covered 
in an agreement a position that had been opposed by the european 
community 
however the draft language also made reference to the european 
communitys more general approach which would measure a countrys 
total trade subsidies and then work to reduce that level thus 
giving each side bargaining space in upcoming talks later this 
month in geneva 
one source said that while this was the language being 
considered for inclusion in the final communique to be read by 
president bush later wednesday negotiators had by no means 
resolved the issue 
they are going through the proposal line by line the source 
said there is still much time left in the evening 
before the trade negotiators began their late night discussions 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said it was uncertain 
whether the united states would achieve its goal of language 
committing countries to acrosstheboard reductions 
the farm subsidy question is still an open one fitzwater 
said 
the dispute over farm subsidies and to a lesser extent 
discussion over soviet aid required the leaders to spend an extra 
90 minutes in their afternoon meeting in addition to bush leaders 
from britain japan west germany canada france italy and a 
representative from the european community were participating in 
the talks 
if the economic summit fails to achieve strong language on the 
farm subsidy issue it would be a significant setback for the bush 
administration which sees resolution of the issue as critical to 
getting global trade talks back on track 
while the united states for three years has been trying to get a 
commitment to eliminate the 245 billion rich countries spend to 
subsidize farmers the european community has been opposed 
contending that 3 million of its farmers could lose their jobs 
the 12 nations of the ec have a total of 10 million farmers 
compared with 2 million in the united states 
the european community has insisted that it was willing to 
reduce the aggregate total of farm subsidies but did not want to 
commit to cutbacks in each separate area sought by the united 
states 
british prime minister margaret thatcher submitted a compromise 
proposal in an effort to bridge the gap but it was rejected by the 
united states as unacceptable officials said even though it 
attracted considerable support from other european countries 
britain which has few smallscale farmers is the most willing 
of the europeans to compromise with the united states and sought to 
mediate in the summit talks 
treasury secretary nicholas brady said the delegations would 
continue discussing the farm dispute late into the night he 
described the debate on agriculture as a vigorous discussion 
among all the countries involved 
president bushs battle to eliminate farm subsidies worldwide 
over the next decade had appeared to receive a boost on monday when 
west german chancellor helmut kohl signaled his willingness to 
accept a usbacked proposal as a starting point for negotiations 
us officials expressed hope that remaining differences could 
be resolved so that the summit countries would be able to give 
guidance to their trade negotiators in geneva 
resolving the farm question is seen as critical to successful 
completion of a nearly fouryear effort to overhaul the global 
trading system that effort known as the uruguay round for the 
country where the talks were launched is being conducted by the 
97nation general agreement on tariffs and trade 
the united states which has posted six consecutive years of 
trade deficits topping 100 billion has a lot riding on the effort 
by removing trade barriers the administration believes a new 
gatt pact would greatly expand export opportunities for american 
businesses and farmers thus lowering the us trade deficit 
the basis for possible compromise in houston revolved around a 
recent outline for a final agreement issued by aart de zeeuw of the 
netherlands the chairman of the gatt agricultural negotiating 
group that proposal calls for significant reductions in subsidies 
for exports in domestic support payments to farmers and the 
removal of barriers to agricultural imports 
west german chancellor helmut kohl expressed support for the de 
zeeuw proposal on monday giving hope to the americans that they 
might be able to convince other european countries to compromise on 
the issue 
but european community officials who have been lobbied hard by 
americans in houston said that while kohls comments were 
significant they did not mean that the other 11 ec countries would 
go along the issue of what position to take was certain to be 
discussed next monday at a meeting of the communitys foreign 
ministers in brussels 
bush had declared that the trade issue was his top priority 
going into the annual economic summit and he argued the point 
forcefully during private oneonone meetings as well as the group 
sessions with his summit partners 
the administration pressed the point that the best thing the 
worlds richest countries could do for the developing world was 
expand trade opportunities especially in agriculture the chief 
export in most of the developing world 
developing countries now lose billions of dollars in sales each 
year because of 245 billion being spent annually to subsidize 
farmers by rich countries us subsidies cost taxpayers and 
consumers 75 billion annually 
the administration believes it can persuade congress to 
eliminate the farm supports over time if other countries do so as 
well since us farmers are among the most efficient in the world 
congress is currently considering a 1990 farm bill which would 
continue americas farm subsidies 
asked tuesday if lawmakers might be willing to cut the subsidies 
if the houston summit reaches agreement on the issue house speaker 
thomas s foley dwash said it is unlikely that congress 
would develop a farm program based on some future circumstance that 
has certainly not yet arrived or not expected to arrive 
