<TEXT>
fbi director william s sessions took his wife 
on 17 business trips aboard government aircraft but she paid for 
only one flight according to a congressional study 
the general accounting office said its survey of trips aboard 
government aircraft by sessions and attorney general dick 
thornburgh underscores the need for a travel policy covering 
federal officials and their spouses 
we continue to believe that a governmentwide policy is needed 
to clarify under what circumstances spouses should be permitted to 
accompany government officials to official functions aboard 
government aircraft said the gao report issued tuesday 
the study of 39 trips aboard government aircraft by thornburgh 
and 36 by sessions between aug 11 1988 and july 31 1989 was 
requested by rep bob wise dwva 
it found that alice sessions accompanied her husband on 17 trips 
to such destinations as san francisco new orleans key west fla 
and williamsburg va 
fbi spokesman robert davenport said mrs sessions did not pay 
for the flights except one because her husband was traveling on 
official business mrs sessions paid 280 for one flight when the 
couple extended a trip to take care of personal business in san 
antonio texas davenport said 
thornburghs wife ginny accompanied her husband on six 
official trips during the period surveyed in april five months 
after the gao began its inquiry thornburgh reimbursed the justice 
department 2128 to cover the six trips plus two others she took 
on government aircraft 
justice department spokesman dan eramian said mrs thornburgh 
was not required to pay for her flights but did so out of an 
abundance of caution 
thornburgh also paid the government 1032 to cover personal 
trips that he and his family took aboard the aircraft which were 
seized from convicted criminals 
gao did not question the propriety of the trips but said the 
government should examine its travel policy to determine when it is 
appropriate for officials to take their spouses on official 
business 
the government should consider what constitutes an official 
purpose or official function and when its appropriate for 
spouses to fly for free gao said 
in a letter to the justice department wise criticized the 
agency for its failure to adopt a travel policy after it had 
assured him last fall that one was being drafted 
eramian said a policy will be adopted adding it would have 
been silly to put something together until we saw what the gao 
recommendations were 
the gao also said the justice department failed to compare the 
cost of using the seized aircraft to transport sessions and 
thornburgh with the cost of leasing private aircraft 
the watchdog arm of congress acknowledged that the justice 
department had legitimate concerns about the security of thornburgh 
and sessions 
but gao said our analysis indicates that private aircraft 
services available through lease charter or rental arrangements 
could satisfy the principal security and related concerns better 
than regularly scheduled airlines 
the justice department did its own analysis after the gao study 
began and concluded that it was saving 500000 a year by using 
seized aircraft instead of leasing commercial planes 
if we had leased an aircraft and spent an extra half million a 
year we would have received a larger dose of criticism eramian 
said 
