<TEXT>
senate employees would get comprehensive 
guarantees against job discrimination for the first time under a 
measure approved by the senate as it launched its debate on a major 
civil rights bill 
but the plan added to the bill tuesday would stop short of 
allowing senate employees to go to court for enforcement of their 
rights prompting complaints that it was out of keeping with the 
spirit of civil rights 
its an appeal to the worst of plantation mentality on capitol 
hill sen charles grassley riowa said in urging a stronger 
version 
senate employees have traditionally been exempted from 
fairhiring and other civil rights guarantees 
the senate itself would handle civil rights complaints from its 
employees under the plan sponsored by sen wendell ford dky but 
it would guarantee them rights under three laws passed over the 
last 25 years and two currently pending including the bill now 
under debate 
provisions of the bill which tops the congressional agenda of 
civil rights forces range from a ban on racial harassment in the 
workplace to a prohibition against discriminatory seniority systems 
the bush administration however has been sharply critical of a 
provision that would force employers either to end discriminatory 
practices or prove in court that they were justified by business 
necessity 
the provision would effectively negate a supreme court ruling 
last year in a case involving hiring practices at a salmon cannery 
in alaska the court held that anyone filing such a suit must prove 
that the discriminatory practice in question was not a business 
necessity 
critics of the bill say its socalled disparate impact 
provisions responding to the ruling would prompt employers to use 
racial and ethnic hiring quotas to head off lawsuits 
administration officials and sen edward m kennedy dmass 
the bills chief sponsor have been searching for a compromise that 
would spare president bush having to veto a civil rights bill and 
give supporters some of their goals 
the negotiations have turned into a fight over shadings of legal 
definitions and no visible progress was made tuesday 
white house chief of staff john h sununu said in a letter to 
kennedy basically i continue to fear language that causes more 
problems than it solves or language with unintended consequences 
that would stimulate a quotabased defensive position 
kennedy issued a statement saying that negotiations are 
continuing but so far the administrations proposals have not been 
satisfactory 
last years decisions by the supreme court have seriously 
jeopardized the right of millions of women and minorities to equal 
job opportunity he said congress should restore the full 
strength of the antidiscrimination law not restore them only part 
way 
earlier kennedy unveiled a fresh compromise proposal saying it 
is a mockery of civil rights for opponents of this 
legislation to raise the false hue and cry of quotas 
but sen orrin hatch rutah said the plan would force 
business people to proportionately hire just to save their skins 
and avoid lawsuits 
the latest round of modifications were refinements of highly 
technical language in the bill for example the revised version 
would force those filing suits to single out specific objectionable 
practices rather than target groups of practices 
the new version would change the definition of business 
necessity from essential to effective job performance to 
bears a substantial and demonstrable relationship to effective 
job performance 
