<TEXT>
the american red cross disputes a report that 
it improperly failed to report on aids cases possibly transmitted 
through blood transfusions and federal authorities acknowledge 
there is no such reporting requirement 
red cross spokesman bud good responded tuesday in a prepared 
statement to a report that the red cross failed to notify federal 
authorities about 228 cases in which patients may have gotten aids 
through contaminated blood transfusions 
the red cross has not failed to comply with fda requirements 
to report transfusionassociated aids cases for the simple reason 
that there are no such requirements good said 
a lowlevel fda report on an inspection of red cross national 
headquarters in washington between april 26 and may 25 found that 
none of the cases had been reported to the agency as required 
but top fda officials acknowledged tuesday that the inspection 
report which was disclosed in tuesdays editions of the 
philadelphia inquirer was incorrect and that there is no federal 
requirement for the red cross to report possible 
transfusionrelated aids cases to the fda 
physicians are supposed to report aids cases to the federal 
centers of disease control 
the lowerlevel fda inspection report that started the flap said 
the red cross lacks procedures for reviewing and tracking 
transfusion associated aids cases 
fda headquarters said in a statement late in the day that the 
agency will pursue these matters and work to remedy any 
problems raised by the inspection report 
however the fda said it had reviewed about 50 of the most 
recent 228 cases of possible transfusionrelated aids and found 
that nearly all involved transfusions before aids antibody testing 
began in 1985 
in the course of the inspection there was no evidence that 
any blood that tested positive after 1985 was improperly 
released the fda said 
the fda also said that past recordkeeping problems of the red 
cross do not show an imminent hazard to the blood supply 
