<DOCNO> AP900711-0044 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
with the smack of a sake bottle japanese 
shipbuilders today christened the worlds first ship that will use 
superconductivity to push itself through the water 
the hightech ship christened the yamato no 1 is a public and 
privately funded experimental vessel shaped roughly like a 
streamlined telephone 
the ships developers said they view the vessel as a prototype 
for highspeed seacraft it will use electromagnetic force instead 
of a conventional screw propeller to thrust itself through the 
water 
the main purpose of the project however is to demonstrate that 
superconductivity could be used to power a ship they said 
this ship has been developed without regard to cost its 
experimental said jutaro namba a coordinator at mitsubishi 
heavy industries in kobe a major port in western japan about 270 
miles west of tokyo 
the 185ton ship is 100 feet long and about 35 feet wide 
it is drydocked in the kobe shipyard of mitsubishi heavy 
industries japans largest shipbuilder and a member of a 
consortium developing the ships new technology 
superconductivity is expected to make the use of electricity 
much more efficient reducing the need for fossil fuels it is 
being developed for use in computers and their components in 
magnetically levitated highspeed trains electric cars and other 
devices 
superconducting coils made of niobium and titanium in thrusters 
underneath the ship are used to create a magnetic field that is 
repulsed by an electric current carried in water circulating 
through the thrusters the repulsion produces the same kind of 
force used to propel superconducting trains on land 
engineers who worked on the ship say a combination of helium gas 
and liquid nitrogen is used to cool the coils to minus 45247 
degrees fahrenheit at that temperature electricity passes through 
the coils without resistance 
the use of waterpropelled thrusters instead of conventional 
rotating screw propellers is expected to minimize maintenance 
problems as well as noise and vibration 
the vessel also is energyefficient most of the space on board 
the ship is occupied however by dieselengine generators used to 
provide an electric current for the thrusters for pumps and for 
onboard equipment the engineers said 
the ships main handicap at present is its speed a mere 8 
knots compared with about 40 knots for fast hydroplanes and to 
minimize its weight it has space for only about 10 people 
experts say new materials are needed to produce a strong enough 
magnetic field to propel the ship at commercially viable speeds 
officials say sea trials will be held next spring after the ship 
is fitted with thrusters and other seagoing equipment a smaller 
model of the ship first was successfully tested in 1987 
the vessel is the brainchild of a consortium of companies 
universities and government researchers led by the japan foundation 
for shipbuilding advancement with funding from the ministry of 
transport 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

