the rules establish secretballot elections of local delegates 
who in turn will nominate candidates for the teamsters 
international board at the 1991 convention also by secret ballot 
the board will be elected by a rank and file vote again by secret 
ballot 
if successful the election would be the first secretballot 
vote in the history of a union which has been the historic 
marionette of organized crime edelstein said 
the election rules stem from the settlement in march 1989 of the 
governments civil racketeering lawsuit against the teamsters the 
settlement was intended to rid the 17 millionmember union of 
corruption and establish new voting procedures 
in adopting the election rules edelstein overruled objections 
by the union that the new voting system gave a courtappointed 
administrator too much power over the union and its locals 
at an earlier point in his opinion the judge said he approved 
rules that guaranteed elections completely secure from 
harassment intimidation coercion hooliganism threats or any 
