a moderate earthquake shook parts of 
southeast alaska and the southwest corner of the yukon early today 
but no damage or injuries were reported 
paul whitmore of the alaska tsunami warning center said the 
quake registered a preliminary magnitude of 57 on the richter 
scale too weak to generate a tsunami or seismic sea wave 
the quake was relatively shallow about nine miles beneath the 
surface and was centered about 40 miles northwest of haines 
alaska whitmore said 
it was felt strongly in haines and also was widely noticed in 
juneau and in whitehorse the yukon territorial capital he said 
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on 
seismographs every increase of one number means a tenfold increase 
in magnitude thus a reading of 75 reflects an earthquake 10 times 
stronger than one of 65 
an earthquake of 5 on the richter scale can cause considerable 
damage and 6 can be severe 
the quake that killed 131 people in 1964 in alaska registered 
84 on the richter scale 
