the nato summit took us toward a more peaceful world a 
british spokesman said on behalf margaret thatcher she believes 
this takes us to a more prosperous world 
a senior us official who has played a prominent role in 
framing administration policy put it this way 
there is a potential for a new economic relationship between 
the soviets and the industrial west i wouldnt say the 
relationship is there yet but what gorbachev gets out of this 
summit is a clear unequivocal affirmation of the belief of the 
seven that it is incumbent upon the west to help perestroika 
succeed 
reflecting the official concluded what this says is that 
were serious about this we would not be going through this effort 
and analysis otherwise 
unthinkable only last july when gorbachev knocked on the summit 
door and was brushed aside as a communist intruder the united 
states britain france west germany japan italy and canada have 
themselves crossed a threshold 
they emerged from this years summit in sunbaked houston 
itself a testimony to nervy free enterprise dedicated to 
perestroika and committed to invest in gorbachevs success 
theres a common determination that we have to respond very 
positively to mr gorbachevs request for a sustained economic 
dialogue between the soviet union and the group of seven 
canadian foreign minister joe clark said 
in declaring nuclear weapons a highly unlikely last resort the 
nato allies in their 41st year moved beyond containment toward one 
europe 
in committing themselves to help gorbachev in practical 
ways the summit leaders blurred the 45year divide between 
capitalism and communism 
at the start the industrialized democracies will take measured 
steps beginning with a study conducted by bankers and other 
experts of the inefficient soviet economy and the tentative moves 
by gorbachev over his five years in power toward freemarket 
reforms 
the study under the supervision of the international monetary 
fund is supposed to be completed by december although officials 
at the world bank said a year would be more like it 
in the meantime a tide of technical assistance is likely to 
flow west to east 
at this stage bush is reluctant to go further he wants the 
soviets to cut military spending abandon cuba and convert to a 
genuine freemarket system the summit agreed and so if these 
conditions are met bush may brave political fire from his right 
and propose more significant us aid 
i dont think you should ever say never secretary of state 
james a baker iii said tuesday in refusing to permanently rule out 
direct us aid 
and will gorbachev be pleased with the results of this summit 
i think he will find in the response a positive encouragement 
to persist in his reforms and that seems to us all the essential 
point douglas hurd the british foreign secretary concluded 
</TEXT>
