<TEXT>
here are excerpts from the final communique 
issued by the leaders of the seven industrial nations at the 
conclusion of their 16th economic summit 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
1 we the heads of state and government of the seven major 
industrial democracies and the president of the commission of the 
european communities meeting in houston for our annual economic 
summit celebrate the renaissance of democracy throughout much of 
the world we welcome unreservedly the spread of multi party 
democracy the practice of free elections the freedom of 
expression and assembly the increased respect for human rights 
the rule of law and the increasing recognition of the principles 
of the open and competitive economy these events proclaim loudly 
mans inalienable rights when people are free to choose they 
choose freedom 
2 the profound changes taking place in europe and progress 
toward democracy elsewhere give us great hope for a world in which 
individuals have increasing opportunities to achieve their economic 
and political aspirations free of tyranny and oppression 
3 we are mindful that freedom and economic prosperity are 
closely linked and mutually reinforcing sustainable economic 
prosperity depends upon the stimulus of competition and the 
encouragement of enterprise on incentives for individual 
initiative and innovation on a skilled and motivated labor force 
whose fundamental rights are protected on sound monetary systems 
on an open system of international trade and payments and on an 
environment safeguarded for future generations 
4 around the world we are determined to assist other peoples 
to achieve and sustain economic prosperity and political freedom 
we will support their efforts with our experience resources and 
goodwill 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
5 in recent years substantial progress has been achieved in 
promoting a stronger world economy through sound macro economic 
policies and greater economic efficiency the economic expansion of 
our countries now in its eighth year has supported notable income 
growth and job creation in the context of rapid growth of 
international trade however unemployment remains high in a number 
of countries inflation although considerably lower than in the 
early 1980s is a matter of serious concern in some countries and 
requires continued vigilance external imbalances have been reduced 
in the united states and japan whereas in other cases they have 
increased continuing adjustment remains a priority in order to 
counter protectionist pressures alleviate uncertainties in 
financial and exchange markets and contribute to avoiding 
pressures on interest rates sound domestic macroeconomic policies 
which may differ according to conditions in each country will make 
a major contribution to further external adjustment 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900711-0098 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
impeached gov evan mecham was back in court 
today defending his right to run again for the office from which 
he was removed in 1988 
mechams candidacy is being challenged by dennis ingram an 
exhighway patrolman who maintains that mechams impeachment and 
subsequent conviction disqualified him from ever again seeking 
public office in arizona 
the state supreme court heard oral arguments on the challenge 
this morning 
the senate convicted mecham in april 1988 of two of the charges 
filed against him by the house and voted 1713 to invoke the 
socalled dracula clause which would have banned him from 
seeking office in the future 
but under the rules of the impeachment trial it would have 
taken a twothirds majority or 20 votes to invoke the clause 
arguments before the supreme court centered on language in the 
constitution limiting the senate to removal of the convicted 
officer and disqualification from holding office in the future 
ingrams lawyer michael meehan argued that the language makes 
both actions mandatory but mechams attorney donald macpherson 
said the language mandates only removal from office and that 
disqualification is discretionary 
vice chief justice stanley feldman acknowledged that the 
constitutional language is unclear 
dont you think one could read this clause either way that 
it is automatic or not he asked its just not clear 
both macpherson and lisa hauser who represented the attorney 
generals office and the secretary of state agreed that if the 
court finds that the language is ambiguous that it must rule for 
mecham 
justice james moeller told meehan that had the senate believed 
that mechams convinction would have resulted not only in his 
removal from office but his permanent disqualification from 
seeking office there might have been a different verdict 
how do we know what the vote would have been on impeachment 
had they known it would forever bar he asked 
chief justice francis x gordon jr who presided over mechams 
impeachment trial disqualified himself from hearing ingrams 
challenge 
feldman said the justices usually rule on such cases the same 
day that arguments are heard but he said the ruling may not come 
that soon in this case and promised only that there would be a 
