<TEXT>
a pair of northern spotted owls is causing 
problems for environmental groups who want to hold a concert in the 
forest 
the us forest service says the event would disturb two spotted 
owls near the concert site the fifth annual concert in the forest 
is set for aug 2426 in the willamette national forest 60 miles 
southeast of portland 
sponsors include friends of the breitenbush cascades and friends 
of the cathedral forest both groups are active in the fight to 
protect old growth forests the habitat of spotted owls from 
logging 
jim farrell a willamette national forest biologist said 
recently that a survey turned up a breeding pair of spotted owls 
with two owlets 1000 to 1500 feet south of the concert site 
the northern spotted owl will be listed as a threatened species 
under federal law on july 23 us fih and wildlife guidelines for 
protecting the owl prohibit activities such as the concert near 
nests farrell said 
however environmentalists say the music is primarily acoustic 
and they contend that the crowd which has reached 700 in past 
years will not pose a threat to the owls 
its an ironic slap to use the owl as a pretext to stop a 
lowimpact event said mark ottenad of friends of the breitenbush 
cascades 
sponsors said they would go ahead with the concert whether or 
not they receive the required forest service permit the event has 
been widely publicized in newsletters and outdoor magazines 
sponsors have rejected three alternate sites the preferred site 
is close to trails and offers views of the cascading south 
breitenbush river and many types of forest from young reforested 
stands to centuriesold groves 
