<TEXT>
however quarrelsome the western industrial 
giants took a historic and probably irreversible turn at their 16th 
economic summit toward a permanent postcold war relationship with 
the soviet union 
president bush and his six partners agreed mikhail gorbachev was 
entitled to their assistance they argued over details how much 
how soon what in return 
but they agreed on immediate technical assistance and dispatched 
a study team to recommend how to target future aid they gave west 
germany the green light to complete a 31 billion loan and aid 
from the others will surely follow 
overall it is a giant leap toward trust after decades of cold 
war suspicion and brinksmanship 
the summit urged gorbachev to take more radical steps to 
shift billions now spent on the red army and on cuba into the sad 
soviet domestic economy hes probably planning to do this anyway 
in his drive to improve living conditions and hold to the levers of 
power 
if gorbachev succeeds in this he stands to gain meaningful 
and sustained economic assistance the windup summit communique 
said 
it was the wests second philosophical swing within a week not 
as dramatic perhaps as natos decision to reduce its reliance on 
