<TEXT>
leaders of the worlds seven richest democracies 
today reached a lastminute compromise on government payments to 
farmers in hopes of giving a push to stalled efforts to overhaul 
the world trading system 
president bush and the other leaders winding up their annual 
economic summit endorsed the compromise language in a short 
morning session the deal between the united states and its 
european trading partners had been arranged during an allnight 
bargaining session among negotiators 
bush said at a midday news conference he hoped the compromise 
would help efforts to reach a broad international trade agreement 
in negotiations that have been going on for four years 
the summit agreement called for acrosstheboard cuts in all 
categories of farm subsidies as demanded by the united states but 
it also contained less specific language that was more acceptable 
to the europeans 
bush acknowledged that there will be some political 
opposition in the united states to phasing out subsidies at home 
but when asked if he would press for such action he said 
absolutely we have to do it 
noting that no quick action was expected in europe he said of a 
us effort thats a little down the road 
the final language in the communique urged each nation to make 
substantial progressive reductions in the areas of export 
subsidies internal price supports and barriers to imports 
the compromise also contained a european demand that it be 
allowed to work out a formula to measure and then reduce a 
variety of farm subsidies this measuring mechanism had been 
opposed by the americans 
the leaders pledged to maintain a high level of personal 
involvement to bring a successful end to the uruguay round of 
international trade talks in december 
the farm fight had been a major focus in the three days of talks 
between the heads of government of the united states japan west 
germany france italy canada and britain the summit was held on 
the campus of rice university the sessions were also attended by a 
representative from the 12nation european community 
we consider the text in general as a satisfactory outcome of 
this meeting said a community official demanding anonymity 
everybody has got something out of it 
a british official hailed the farm agreement and said prime 
minister margaret thatcher believed it would mean a successful 
windup of the world trade talks 
bush had made achieving progress on farm subsidies a top 
priority at this years summit believing that without movement on 
farm subsidies an ambitious effort to rewrite the rules governing 
world trade could be doomed 
the united states has a lot riding on the 96nation uruguay 
round talks the president has said they offer the best hope of 
expanding export opportunities for us farmers and businesses and 
thus reducing americas huge trade deficits 
bush spoke forcefully during the sessions but he faced strong 
resistance from european countries who contended that his 
insistence on complete elimination of all tradedistorting farm 
subsidies could end up costing the jobs of up to 3 million farmers 
the leaders had extended their afternoon session on tuesday for 
an extra 90 minutes grappling with the farm subsidy issue finally 
sending lower level negotiators off to work through the night in an 
attempt to come up with compromise language 
the draft agreement specifically mentions reductions in the 
three areas of farm subsidies targeted by the united states for 
cuts these include export subsidies internal price supports and 
barriers to imported goods 
the united states had insisted that the areas be spelled out in 
any agreement despite opposition from the european community 
but in an effort to bridge the gap between the two sides the 
agreement also refers to the communitys more general approach to 
cutting subsidies which employs a technical yardstick to measure 
subsidy levels 
the global trade negotiations which opened in 1986 in uruguay 
are due to wind up with a final round of hard bargaining in early 
december in brussels belgium 
european community officials have long fought to protect their 
expensive export subsidies they contend that getting rid of the 
program would translate into higher farm prices in europe and 
result in the loss of jobs for millions of farmers 
the program gives exporters help so more highpriced european 
farm products can compete with lower prices on the world market 
the united states has responded by setting up its own export 
enhancement program 
american officials also have pressed the community to open its 
markets wider to foreign farm products and reduce farm payments 
that encourage overproduction of crops 
the uruguay round is being held under the auspices of the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade a forum and agreement for 
promoting freer trade 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

