<TEXT>
the medicare program pays at least 400 
million annually for medical services that should instead be 
covered by private insurance plans a federal official told a 
senate subcommittee wednesday 
michael mangano a deputy inspector general at the department of 
health and human services testified the money is being lost 
because the medicare program does not ensure that companies that 
insure people who also receive medicare pay the primary cost of 
their medical bills 
he estimated the annual loss at between 400 million and 600 
million based on 1988 data but added that is a very 
conservative estimate 
sen william roth rdel ranking member of the senate 
government affairs investigations subcommittee said other 
estimates put the loss as high as 1 billion a year and called the 
problem absolutely astounding 
it gives lie to claims that the federal government needs to 
raise taxes to make its budgetary ends meet said roth until 
we get our house in order on the waste fraud and abuse that cost 
the taxpayers so dearly we have no right to ask these same 
taxpayers to shell out even more in taxes 
mangano said his office has recommended that the health care 
financing administration which handles medicare improve efforts 
to determine when beneficiaries are also covered by private 
insurance although hcfa has taken some actions agency officials 
have not eliminated the problems he said 
the 105 million medicare program helps pay the medical expenses 
for about 34 million americans who are 65 and older or are disabled 
the subcommittee focused on one insurance company provident 
life and accident insurance co which roth said allegedly 
followed a deliberate policy of evading payments on claims of 
patients they had insured by foisting these claims off on 
medicare 
the inspector generals office recommended government action 
against the company but the justice department declined to 
prosecute due to manpower shortages and because other remedies 
were available mangano said 
larry simmons of the inspector generals office said the inquiry 
and internal company memos show providents strategy appeared to be 
that they would not pay until someone told them to 
winston w walker president of the chattanooga tennbased 
insurance company testified that the blame was medicares alone 
our company was prepared to pay as primary payer but its 
efforts to determine how much and when to pay a claim were 
rebuffed by medicare officials he said 
he said medicare has no procedures to identify beneficiaries 
with other insurance coverage before it pays a claim 
medicare and an insurance plan often both paid benefits to 
healthcare providers or beneficiaries he said medicare then 
expected the recipient to volunteer to repay medicare the amount 
overpaid he said 
provident did not cause this breakdown and provident cannot 
fix it walker said only the government can fix it and then 
only by implementing rational administrative procedures 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

