a consumer group petitioned federal 
authorities wednesday to force a heartvalve manufacturer to warn 
56000 people living with the implanted device about the valves 
defects 
public citizen wants the irvine califbased shiley inc a 
subsidiary of pfizer inc to notify all those who have had the 
device implanted about the symptoms and consequences of a failed 
valve the group also wants the company to advise patients of the 
risks and benefits of having the valve removed 
the company has reported to the fda more than 250 deaths that 
have resulted from fractures of the valve 
public citizen asked the fda to order the company to send a 
notice to each person who has had a shiley valve implanted 
describing the signs and symptoms of imminent valve failure 
the notice also would list each hospital in the united states 
where open heart surgery is performed so patients would know where 
to go for emergency valve replacement surgery 
public citizen filed suit against the company in march to force 
the company to notify patients directly but the suit was dismissed 
in los angeles county superior court public citizen has filed an 
appeal 
robert j fauteux a spokesman for shiley said the company has 
followed the fdas policy on the matter which recommends that 
companies communicate with patients through their physicians 
shiley has kept physicians of patients with shiley valves 
updated on the devices problems on a regular basis since 1980 he 
said 
the fda is reviewing its recommendation on how to get 
information to patients and if the fda were to reconsider its 
policy shiley would reassess our policy fauteux said 
fda spokesman jeff nesbit said agency officials would review 
public citizens petition 
