<TEXT>
harvard university plans to purchase 
about 5 million ecuadoran debt to fund a pioneering scholarship 
program aimed at easing the countrys financial burdens officials 
said wednesday 
its a rather special situation that provides a model that 
could be built on for other countries in similar circumstances 
harvard president derek c bok said 
the elaborate debtforscholarship swap essentially takes a 
loselose situation and turns it into an allaround winner by 
converting a portion of ecuadors 11 billion foreign debt into 
cash for education the coloradosized south american countrys 
debt burden gets reduced its us creditors get rid of bonds they 
fear will never be repaid and harvard gets some of ecuadors top 
scholars 
harvard is the only one i know of doing this said robert h 
scott the schools vice president for finance 
scott worked with ecuadoran vice president luis parodi in 
developing the program the agreement was signed here monday 
heres how it works 
harvard purchases 5 million of ecuadoran debt for 750000 in 
the form of discounted loan certificates from us banks eager to 
remove the loans from their books 
the university then donates the certificates to the fundacion 
capacitar an ecuadoran education fund which can exchange them 
locally at the nations central bank for government bonds worth 50 
percent of the loans face value or about 25 million 
fundacion capacitar then sells the bonds on the securities 
market for 25 million in local currency which is then invested 
in dollardenominated securities that will be used as an endowment 
to support harvard scholarships for about 70 ecuadoran students 
during the next 10 years 
the 100000 to 200000 annual scholarships were expected to 
fund five to eight ecuadoran students at harvard by the fall of 
1991 officials said 
this is a very attractive way to develop a financial base to 
provide for the financial aid costs of students from ecuador 
said bok who has announced he will leave harvard next year after 
20 years as president 
through the debtswap were able to leverage the investment we 
make by several times in order to provide a larger fund 
harvard officials said they plan to discuss creating similar 
programs in other latin american countries 
gerard cassidy a bank analyst with tucker anthony inc in 
boston predicted many commercial lenders would be eager to sell 
their debt in secondary markets even at depressed prices 
its a creative way of solving a very difficult situation 
he said its not a panacea but it shows the kind of 
creativeness that is needed 
such debtswap plans have cropped up in several latin american 
nations in recent years many have been funded by northern european 
and us environmental groups who want to protect rain forests and 
national parks 
the nice thing about these conversions is that they foster 
some social goals that governments havent always been able to 
address because theyve been financially strapped said tom 
fullerton an economist with the wefa group formally wharton 
econometrics of bala cynwyd pa 
the ecuadoran government has in recent years been looking for a 
way out of the debt it accrued in the mid1980s when world oil 
prices dropped and an earthquake severed a transandean pipeline 
through the nation of about 10 million people 
ecuadoran officials are negotiating a debtrestructuring program 
that would could reduce their interest rates or up to 70 percent of 
the principal owed 
fullerton said the scholarship plan was a step in the right 
direction but cautioned that it will dissolve only a fraction of 
ecuadors hefty debt which includes 6 billion owed to foreign 
commercial banks 
the amount that were dealing with is very small compared with 
total ecuadoran debt overseas he said but it addresses an 
important social goal and will help improve the human capital 
available in ecuador 
</TEXT>
