<TEXT>
six weeks of hot dry weather have seared 
corn soybean cotton and tobacco crops in the southeast but farm 
experts looked hopefully for weekend rains that could avert an 
agricultural disaster 
karl harker an agricultural meteorologist with the national 
weather service at auburn university in alabama said a low 
pressure system will move into the region as early as thursday 
increasing the likelihood of showers and thunderstorms 
my farm is on irrigation but our water supply is gone said 
albert johnson who owns a 53acre farm in south carolina the 
extreme heat is making tobacco do things that ive never seen 
before the tobacco is literally baking 
georgia agriculture commissioner tommy irvin said without 
significant rain in the next two weeks farmers could face their 
worst disaster since the 1986 drought 
were at a crossroads he said if it doesnt improve we 
stand to be worse than then 
irvin said farmers need a break in the heat and two or three 
days of light showers to soak the ground 
harker said 30day rainfall totals in georgia are running 2 to 6 
inches below normal 
the weather service said north carolina averaged 125 inches in 
june instead of the usual four inches 
south carolina has shortfalls of two to five inches according 
to the southeast regional climate center in columbia sc 
the centers director john purvis said tennessee also has been 
dry nashvilles shortfall is 914 inches since jan 1 
irvin said the drought has severely damaged georgias corn crop 
has killed soybean plants and is expected to substantially reduce 
cotton yields 
it has also lowered milk production forced farmers to feed 
their cattle hay normally reserved for winter has lowered egg 
production and has reduced the weight of chickens 
south carolina officials said corn tobacco and soybeans have 
been hardest hit 
joe burns a crop specialist with the university of tennessee 
agricultural extension service estimated that farmers in eastern 
tennessee are losing about 400000 bushels of corn a day or about 
1 million a day because of the drought 
tobacco the main cash crop in eastern tennessee have virtually 
stopped growing said charles farmer an extension service 
economist 
its an iffy situation farmer said i think we can still 
make some good crops if we get some moisture pretty soon but 
obviously we have lost some ground 
north carolinas tobacco crop is protected by irrigation on most 
farms but corn has withered in some fields officials said most 
of the states 125 million acres of corn is in the hardhit 
eastern part of the state 
columbus county extension director garland mcmullen said farmers 
in his county will lose about half their corn 
we have some areas the farmers will not be able to harvest 
at all he said theres no ears on the stalk 
carl cross a statistician with the north carolina agriculture 
department in raleigh said only an eighth of the states corn crop 
was rated good this week compared to onethird last week 
