<TEXT>
energy secretary james watkins said wednesday 
his department will take more direct control of the contaminated 
hanford nuclear reservation as part of a plan to clean up problems 
at the nations nuclear weapons program 
we are changing the way of doing business at one of our major 
facilities this is the first of a number of shoes to drop 
watkins said at a news conference 
in addition to taking a greater government role in managing the 
hanford site at washington state watkins said the energy 
department will enter a new agreement with the army corps of 
engineers on thursday to help clean up radioactive wastes at the 
nations nuclear weapons plants 
watkins said he was extremely disappointed with the 
condition of the nuclear weapons plants when he initiated a 30year 
cleanup plan about 18 months ago 
it was a shock to me i had no idea we had not learned the 
lessons of three mile island he said now is the time to pay 
the piper and clean up 40 years of waste 
the department announced last week it was increasing its 
estimate of the cleanup costs nationally to nearly 30 billion over 
the next five years 
watkins said wednesday the boost was due partly to budget 
officials who fear they will be subject to lawsuits if they dont 
ask for enough cleanup money and partly to the discovery of 
additional contamination 
watkins said the work one official currently performs at hanford 
will be handled by three deputies under his new management plan 
including one who will be directly responsible for waste cleanup 
also under the new plan the new site manager john wagoner will 
report directly to the director of the departments office of 
environmental restoration and waste management wagoner deputy 
manager of the savannah river facility the past two years replaces 
hanford site manager mike lawrence who resigned last week to take 
another job 
now we will have direct reporting from one of our major 
sites watkins said 
the hanford site along the columbia river near richland wash 
contains 600000 cubic yards of radioactive waste watkins said 
disclosures in recent years show that dangerous contaminants 
were released directly into the air water and soil 
watkins said the energy department which oversees the nations 
nuclear weapons plants is trying to upgrade plant operations by 
adding workers and administrators directly charged with improving 
of safety 
we need people in the plant walking looking being sensitive 
to the health issues on a sevenday a week 24hour a day basis 
he said none of thats been done in the past that is one of the 
reasons weve been targeted and targeted so successfully by groups 
who have legitimate complaints against us 
watkins said details of the memo of understanding with the army 
corps of engineers will be made available on thursday he said more 
specific plans for the agreement at hanford are expected over the 
next week with other sitespecific plans to follow in the future 
