the house approved wednesday a bill 
authorizing 290 million for the national institute of standards 
and technology and expanding government technology programs 
the bill would authorize 50 million this year and 100 million 
next year for the advanced technology program established in 1988 
trade legislation to promote industrial consortiums in hightech 
areas such as highdefinition television superconductivity and 
advanced manufacturing 
it would authorize 250 million in fiscal 1992 for that 
technology program president bush had requested only 10 million 
for the progam and republicans mounted an unsuccessful effort to 
strip the 250 million 1992 authorization from the bill 
the house voted 327 to 93 to approve the bill 
grants under the advanced technology program would be awarded to 
research ventures on technology important for various industries 
but which no single company is likely to undertake on its own 
sponsors said the commerce department would be required to 
negotiate agreements to ensure the govermment receives a return on 
its investment 
