<TEXT>
the 15 republic communist party leaders to become 
politburo members under new rules adopted by the party congress 
include traditionalists and reformers most want a deal with the 
kremlin to give the regions more autonomy 
following are thumbnail sketches 
armenia vladimir movsisyan took office in april succeeding a 
strong armenian nationalist born in 1935 he has spent his entire 
career in armenia specializing in agriculture he is thought to be 
a traditionalist inclined toward reforms including more 
sovereignty for the republics 
azerbaijan ayaz n mutalibov leads a republic that has been 
under martial law for six months due to ethnic rioting mutalibov 
was elected in january after his predecessor was expelled from the 
party an economist and technocrat mutalibov worked at a household 
appliance factory in the republics capital of baku before 
switching to party work in 1977 in a 1989 interview in the 
government newspaper izvestia he was quoted as saying it was 
necessary to strengthen the economy before tackling social problems 
such as unemployment 
byelorussia yefrem sokolov supports glasnost and advocated 
open discussions of public policy before president mikhail s 
gorbachev came to power in 1985 however byelorussia was one of 
the last republics in which grassroots movements took hold and it 
has acquired a reputation as a conservative backwater 
estonia the estonian communist party plans to split this fall 
into two factions both of which are represented at the congress 
the independent faction is led by chairman vaino vyalyas a former 
ambassador and communist youth league comrade of gorbachevs youth 
and first secretary enn arno sillari the loyalist faction is led 
by alexander gusev it is not known which factions leader would be 
chosen for the politburo 
georgia givi gumbaridze an enthusiastic supporter of 
gorbachev and his reforms was born in 1945 making him one of the 
youngest republic party leaders he was chairman of the kgb in the 
southern republic for four months before taking over the party post 
in april 1989 replacing a leader blamed for permitting a military 
crackdown on demonstrators georgia is pushing for independence and 
has a strong secession movement supported by many republic 
communist leaders 
kazakhstan nursultan nazarbaev supports reforms to give his 
asian republic control of its natural resources and revive its 
language he wants to close the nuclear testing range at 
semipalatinsk born in 1940 and trained as a technocrat he 
advanced rapidly in the party and was elected first secretary in 
june 1989 speaking to the congress he pleaded for clearer 
direction from the kremlin likening current policy to an army 
that is retreating in haste without a plan 
kirghizia absomat masaliyev is a traditionalist who feels 
party leaders have not adequately defended the party from critical 
attacks he called for the safeguarding of communist ideals saying 
anything else would be a betrayal of whole generations of 
communists he repeatedly quoted lenin to a congress that has 
otherwise rarely referred to its former leader 
latvia alfreds rubiks 54 was listed by a latvian youth 
magazine in 1988 and 1989 as one of the most unpopular men in his 
small baltic republic a career party worker rubiks came to 
prominence as mayor of the capital city of riga in 1984 rubiks 
opposed latvias independence declaration in may the republics 
communist party has split and rubiks leads the majority promoscow 
faction he complained at the congress that communist parties were 
too eager to make compromises with other groups 
lithuania mikolas burakevicius a hardliner represents a 
closeknit communist group opposed to independence his faction is 
greatly outnumbered by the proindependence faction led by algirdas 
brazauskas which was not invited to the party congress 
moldavia pyotr luchinsky a reformer is a native of moldavia 
which shares language and culture with bordering romania and which 
has declared itself sovereign with the right to overturn national 
laws luchinsky who took office in november 1989 says the earlier 
the 15 republics obtain full selfreliance the faster ethnic 
tensions will subside the son of peasants luchinsky studied 
history and philosophy before launching a career in moldavias 
young communist league he worked in the partys propaganda 
department in moscow and was secondsecretary in tajikistan before 
returning to moldavia 
russian federation ivan polozkov 55 swept to power on a tide 
of conservatism last month at the reconstitution of the russian 
wing of the party the previous month he narrowly lost the russian 
presidency to boris yeltsin as party leader in the southern 
russian region of krasnodar polozkov gained attention for a 
vigorous campaign against cooperatives the small privately held 
businesses permitted under gorbachevs reforms polozkov an 
economist says hes not as conservative as critics claim 
tadzhikistan kakhar makhkamov complained to the congress that 
new social groups and parties criticize the communist party without 
taking any responsibility themselves for societys problem he 
advocated a strong party and implied it was still virtually 
indivisible from the government however he backed more 
independence for republic parties and defended gorbachev 
turkmenia sappar niyazov appears to be a centrist trying to 
steer a middle course on perestroika but occasionally veers to the 
right 
ukraine stanislav gurenko the newly elected party chief in 
the secondlargest republic warned congress delegates not to 
underestimate the dangers of anticommunism we should rebuff 
mudslinging slander we should not retreat from our positions we 
should stop committing suicide we should stop this 
selfflagellation gurenko faces anticommunist challenges in the 
don river coalmining basin in the eastern ukraine and in the 
western region near lvov 
uzbekistan islam karimov 52 gave a cautious speech to the 
congress mildly criticizing central authorities for their handling 
of ethnic disputes he said he supported gorbachev as party leader 
but felt the party should not deviate from its core policy of 
democratic centralism 
</TEXT>
