<TEXT>
seeking an objective opinion of where financial 
markets are headed fidelity investments one of the worlds 
biggest buyers and sellers of securities has gone to the source 
its asking investors 
while that step might not seem revolutionary it is decidedly 
the opposite of how the marketplace usually functions more often 
than not most popularly circulated opinions originate with brokers 
rather than investors 
wall streeters are prolific advisers dispensing a flood of 
opinions every minute hour and day about almost any subject known 
or unknown to them the primary purpose of which is to keep the 
market active and remunerative 
whether it accomplishes the latter is a moot point since the 
proliferation of opinion comes at a great cost in credibility 
in contrast there is probably no opinion more solid than that 
of buyers or potential buyers whose views are based on their own 
financial condition expectations and ability to buy or sell 
it is into this mine of data that fidelity is delving to create 
its survey of individual investors a statistical measurement of 
investor sentiments and expectations including intentions three 
months into the future 
good news or poor fidelity will have to live with results of 
the survey because it is being conducted and controlled by the 
university of michigans survey research center already noted for 
surveys of consumer sentiment 
sindlinger amp co a wallingford pa marketing and research 
firm already produces similar surveys for clients but this is the 
first time a worldwide marketer of securities which fidelity is 
has entered the field 
the rationale for doing so is that sound surveys of consumer 
sentiment and expectations already have demonstrated that a 
relationship exists between consumer expectations and actual 
changes that later occur in the economy 
that relationship has been demonstrated for example in the 
areas of interest rates unemployment levels inflation rates 
gross national product homebuying and vehicle purchases why not 
securities too 
fidelitys questions were added to the michigan survey in 
january so as yet there is little historical record with which to 
make comparisons but in those few months of existence some 
significant findings have emerged 
michael hines fidelity vice president for marketing points 
out for example that junes investor expectations were 
encouraging since investor households measured significantly 
higher than households in general 
another important finding was that after four straight months of 
expecting interest rates to rise investors in june said they 
anticipated a decline over the next 12 months 
the survey also found 
established investors continue to view prospects for their own 
financial situation in favorable terms 
among various types of mutual funds owners of money market 
funds are most likely to plan additional investments in the next 
three months 
owners of individual stocks in may seemed to be more content 
with their position than in april fewer were likely to make 
additional investments and fewer were likely to sell 
these are among the first findings released by fidelity 
hereafter said hines detailed results will be issued on a regular 
monthly basis within a week of each surveys completion 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

