<DOCNO> AP900711-0198 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
as they map out strategies for managing their 
personal finances in the 1990s many americans seem to have agreed 
on a common precept put a little less faith in credit 
they havent sworn off borrowing by any means as of may they 
carried no less than 725 billion in credit card balances auto 
loans and other types of consumer debt 
but the growth of borrowing and lending activity which 
sometimes proceeded at a dizzying pace in the 1980s has shown 
distinct signs of slowing 
while that threatens to worsen the various woes of the economy 
in the near future many economists say it could well prove over 
the longer term to be a sensible and beneficial development for all 
concerned 
the cutback on credit often is seen as the result of and a 
necessary response to the borrowing spree of the past decade 
most analysts agree that is a primary force behind the trend 
but see several other important influences as well 
a fundamental shift in attitude towards leverage has occurred 
in the us economy and is being reinforced by government policy 
says richard hoey chief economist in the united states for the 
international investment firm of barclays de zoete wedd inc 
there is both a reduced willingness to demand credit and a 
reduced willingness to supply credit 
the government has played a part on both sides of the equation 
pressure from bank regulators has helped push many lending 
institutions toward extracautious standards in deciding who 
qualifies for a loan 
at the same time tax changes put into effect over the past 
several years seem to be crimping consumers demand for loans 
just a decade ago uncle sam permitted tax deductions that 
subsidized borrowing to the tune of as much as 50 cents for each 1 
in interest that consumers paid now that deduction is worth 33 
cents per dollar of interest at most and it disappears altogether 
next jan 1 
if tax changes make borrowing these days seem more expensive so 
does the relatively high level of interest rates in comparison to 
the inflation rate 
while inflation runs at an annual pace of 4 percent to 5 
percent a car buyer might pay an average of 1229 percent on a 
fouryear 9000 auto loan according to the bank rate monitor 
personal loans and credit card borrowing typically run in the 17 
percent to 19 percent range or higher in some cases 
gone is the incentive that existed in the late 1970s and early 
1980s to borrow freely paying interest costs of nearly nothing 
once inflation was taken into account 
furthermore with the flattening out of the boom in the housing 
market the use of debt as speculative leverage in real estate has 
lost a lot of its appeal 
observers like hoey also say an absence of heady gains in home 
prices has dampened enthusiasm for types of credit other than 
mortgages and construction loans 
we believe that real estate values and the perception of real 
estate liquidity are crucial to consumer confidence he says 
even in the absence of a major change in real estate prices the 
perceived or psychic liquidity of real estate fluctuates 
middleclass balance sheets become less liquid when real 
estate turnover drops putting downward pressure on the willingness 
to spend among consumers 
</TEXT>
