while prime minister petre roman 
pledges to move toward a free economy bucharest police are 
cracking down on the bustling black market 
in a few days last month they arrested 1680 black market 
operators and confiscated goods worth 270000 a police statement 
reported it also said the illegal trade would be eradicated 
but success has been elusive 
the black market is the only source for many items the goods 
often are stolen from factories or stores sometimes with the aid 
of bribed workers 
fighting the trade and the corruption it feeds is made more 
difficult by tolerance of the underground market by a public long 
accustomed to facing shortages in stores and seeking ways around 
them 
after more than four decades of a planned economy and shortages 
of virtually everything romanians are uncertain of how to approach 
a free market 
officials speak proudly of more liberal rules on private 
initiative promulgated since communist dictator nicolae ceausescu 
was deposed and executed in december but say theft and 
profiteering have accompanied freedom 
vasile sebe president of the free trade union in commerce was 
quoted by the daily romania libera as saying free initiative 
must not turn into speculation with products which are scarce 
but should stimulate entrepreneurs to find new sources of 
supplies 
production businesses have been slow to emerge because private 
enterprises are limited to 20 employees and the bureaucracy remains 
cumbersome thievery and the black market have flourished 
police reported the theft of coffee worth 50000 in june and 
said only onefifth of it was recovered 
