<TEXT>
here is a chronology of important events in the wall street 
insider trading scandal leading up to the conviction tuesday of 
exspeculator john a mulheren jr on conspiracy and stock 
manipulation charges 
may 1986 federal authorities arrest dennis levine a managing 
director of drexel burnham lambert inc and accuse him of making 
126 million in illegal profits on insider trading tips 
june 1986 levine pleads guilty and begins implicating a 
number of industry colleagues including ivan f boesky the 
bestknown stock speculator on wall street for extensive insider 
trading abuses and other frauds 
november 1986 boesky settles insider trading charges with the 
securities and exchange commission paying a thenrecord 100 
million in fines and penalties he begins providing extensive 
evidence against some of the most successful names on wall street 
notably junkbond investment giant drexel burnham lambert inc and 
its chief financier michael milken 
february 1987 three leading wall street professionals 
richard b wigton timothy l tabor and robert freeman are 
arrested on insider trading charges based on information indirectly 
stemming from boeskys cooperation a fourth martin a siegel 
agrees to plead guilty and cooperate levine is sentenced to two 
years imprisonment 
march 1987 boyd l jefferies a leading west coast stock 
trader pleads guilty to two criminal counts based on information 
supplied by boesky he agrees to cooperate with investigators 
april 1987 boesky pleads guilty to one criminal charge 
may 1987 criminal charges against wigton tabor and freeman 
are dropped after prosecutors cannot assemble their case without 
more time the government says it will bring a new case 
june 1987 kidder peabody amp co pays a 253 million fine to 
settle insider trading and stock parking charges with the sec 
december 1987 boesky receives a threeyear prison term 
february 1988 police arrest stock speculator john a mulheren 
jr a former boesky confidante and friend after mulheren 
allegedly threatens to kill boesky for implicating him in criminal 
wrongdoing 
march 1988 boesky begins serving federal prison term 
july 1988 gaf corp and its vice chairman james sherwin are 
indicted on stock manipulation charges based on information 
supplied by jefferies they plead innocent 
august 1988 five principals of princetonnewport partners an 
investment partnership with links to drexel are indicted on fraud 
and racketeering counts the first time a punitive racketeering law 
is used to prosecute securities professionals the defendants plead 
innocent but the firm is forced to liquidate 
september 1988 the sec accuses drexel and milken of a wide 
range of civil securities fraud violations based on information 
supplied by boesky they deny the accusations 
november 1988 salim b lewis a wellknown stock speculator 
is indicted on stock manipulation charges based on information 
supplied by jefferies he pleads innocent 
december 1988 drexel agrees to plead guilty to six felonies 
and pay a record 650 million in fines to settle the biggest 
securities fraud case in history paul bilzerian a wellknown 
takeover strategist is indicted based on information supplied by 
jefferies he pleads innocent 
march 1989 milken and two other drexel aides are indicted on 
98 counts of racketeering and fraud largely stemming from 
information supplied by boesky they plead innocent 
april 1989 drexel reaches a civil settlement with the sec 
that subjects the company to unprecendented government supervision 
sowing the seeds of a decline that eventually drives the company 
into bankruptcy reorganization 
june 1989 bilzerian is found guilty mulheren and colleague 
leonard l destefano are indicted on numerous counts of fraud and 
conspiracy based largely on information supplied by boesky they 
plead innocent 
july 1989 jefferies is sentenced to five years probation and 
a 250000 fine princeton newport defendants are found guilty 
august 1989 freeman pleads guilty to a single felony count 
stemming from information supplied by siegel the government drops 
its case against wigton and tabor lewis changes his plea to guilty 
december 1989 after two mistrials a jury convicts gaf and 
sherwin of securities fraud and stock manipulation violations 
lewis is sentenced to probation and community service 
march 1990 sherwin is sentenced to six months imprisonment 
and gaf is fined 2 million 
april 1990 boesky is released from federal custody milken 
capitulates to federal pressure and agrees to plead guilty to six 
felony counts and pay 600 million to settle his case 
may 1990 mulheren and destefano go to trial highlighted by 
the first public testimony from boesky since the wall street 
corruption scandal began 
june 1990 siegel is sentenced to two months imprisonment 
july 1990 a jury convicts mulheren on four counts deadlocks 
on the remaining 26 and acquits destefano the verdict marks the 
first government trial victory in the scandal based on evidence 
supplied by boesky 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

