<TEXT>
inside a cluster of plush buildings 
baked by the silicon valley sun apple computer inc employees 
wearing sport shirts and jeans are readying products they hope will 
revive the companys breathtaking growth 
their casual dress and californiaready smiles belie the 
seriousness of their task to overcome a major challenge to apples 
main product the macintosh and revamp what critics call a tired 
overpriced product line the combination has caused sales growth to 
slow and apples stock price to falter 
the personal computer giant hatched in a garage 14 years ago 
also must dispel the appearance of instability created by recent 
leadership changes 
since january apple lost its productdevelopment chief and the 
president of its domestic marketing operation in addition its top 
us sales executive moved to parttime status and a senior 
scientist who helped develop the macintosh announced earlier this 
month he was quitting to form his own company 
there is nothing technically wrong with apples products and 
it has plenty of room for growth said richard shaffer publisher 
of technologic computer letter an industry newsletter but the 
company has taken too long to get some products out and it has not 
had its marketing act together 
although apple remains one of americas most dynamic and least 
indebted young companies the executive changes havent helped 
answer the persistent question of whos in charge 
you cant have the management turnover like they had at apple 
without problems shaffer said 
last month apple finally named a new president for the domestic 
division an important post vacant for six months robert puette a 
longtime hewlettpackard co executive expressed confidence in his 
new employer 
i think the turmoil is going to pretty well disappear and 
youre going to see some strong marketing messages from the 
company he said 
those messages will be needed since apple must respond to the 
most serious threat yet to the macintoshs primacy 
the 6yearold computer is acclaimed for a graphicsbased 
operating system that makes it easy even for computer novices to 
run the machines as soon as they take them out of the box 
the macintosh popularized the use of an onscreen arrow 
manipulated with a device called a mouse by moving the arrow to 
pictures on the screen and pushing a button on the mouse users can 
open computer files print copies and perform other tasks 
by comparison on most international business machines corp 
computers and ibmcompatible models users must type technical 
commands 
but in may microsoft corp released a muchimproved version of 
a software product called windows which replaces the typed 
commands with userfriendly graphics also manipulated by a mouse 
though the macintosh is still easier to use in some respects 
and windows cant be used on all ibm computers and compatibles 
many analysts believe the new windows gives computer novices and 
others their first real alternative to the macintosh 
another problem facing apple critics say is its pricey 
computers 
the macintosh line is about 25 percent costlier than comparable 
models from ibm and compaq computer corp two major competitors 
said rick martin an analyst at prudentialbache securities inc 
before windows apple could charge a premium for its machines 
because of their relative ease of use martin said 
you take that wide price gap and throw windows on top of it 
and you now have the beginnings of what could be a major problem 
he said 
joeann stahel president of storeboardcomputer intelligence 
said surveys her market research firm takes of computer dealers 
show that lowering the price of macintoshes is a priority 
the dealers were very concered about apples pricing in a 
market where youve got such heavy competiton from the ibm pc 
compatibles she said 
last month ibm announced a new home computer line that could 
spell more trouble for apple the machines feature a mouse and 
onscreen graphics designed to make them easy to use though they 
arent as sophisticated as a macintosh but the low end of the line 
costs 999 vs the cheapest macintosh at 1799 
apple sold 4 billion worth of macintoshes last year by far the 
most important product it offers faced with new assaults apple 
isnt standing still 
later this year the company plans to introduce lowerpriced 
versions of the macintosh with both color and blackandwhite 
screens 
mike homer director of domestic product marketing said a 
lowerpriced macintosh with a color monitor is clearly a hardware 
product hole we have to plug apples cheapest color macintosh 
today lists for 4669 while ibm clones with color screens cost 
thousands less 
to reduce the cost of macintoshes apple most likely will limit 
the number of options on new models and accept a lower profit 
margin said jim davis apples director of operating system 
software 
martin said he expects the new lowend color macintosh will cost 
2000 to 2500 ms stahel said she has heard the lowend 
blackandwhite macintosh will sell for about 1000 apple 
wouldnt comment on pricing plans 
besides lowerpriced computers apple recently introduced 
cheaper laser printers in response to challenges from competitors 
it also is readying a new version of its operating system which 
controls a computers basic functions such as organizing files 
that will enhance the macintoshs performance 
not all apples products need facelifts the company revamped 
the top end of the macintosh line over the past year and says 
sales of these expensive highpowered machines aimed at corporate 
users are strong 
meanwhile apple officials say the hype about windows benefited 
apple since it drew more attention to graphicsbased computing 
systems davis contends the macintosh will win any comparison with 
a windowequipped ibm or compatible computer 
apple executives and industry analysts also point out that the 
library of software that takes advantage of windows capabilities 
is small compared with the several thousand macintosh programs on 
the market 
in coming months apples advertising will more clearly point 
out these differences davis said 
some of the ads in the us were a little fuzzy he said 
shaffer agreed unless apple begins to stress those 
stillimportant differences apple will lose market share he 
said 
infocorp a market research firm that tracks computer sales 
reckons apples sales fell in the first three months of this year 
vs a year earlier but since have picked up analysts say apple 
holds about 10 percent of worldwide personal computer market 
this is hardly apples first slump the companys history has 
been shaped by booms and busts since its founding in a garage by 
steve jobs and steve wozniak in 1976 its current malaise is a mild 
headache compared with the turmoil layoffs and financial losses 
that led to jobs ouster in 1985 
despite the current troubles apples finances are strong the 
company has almost no debt and about 1 billion in cash on hand 
analysts expect its profit will grow at least 10 percent in the 
fiscal year that ends sept 30 
however apples stock price has suffered reflecting some 
pessimism in its ability to continue the quantumleap innovations 
that first made the company a household word in the late 70s 
soon after windows premiered apple shares slumped from the 
mid40s into the high 30s though it recent weeks the stock has 
moved sharply higher 
this company is doing just fine said martin but all the 
turmoil caused investors to be very very nervous 
