conference what he can expect is that well be helpful to him in 
the kinds of reforms that he has to undertake 
bush balked at sending direct us assistance to the soviets and 
repeated his criticism of their 5 billion annual support of 
marxist cuba i think we will send the kind of help that in the 
long run will be most beneficial to them he said 
sending experts abroad to help needy countries known as 
technical assistance in foreignpolicy jargon has been a 
centerpiece of the us foreign aid program for years and now it 
is a feature of the new spirit of cooperation between the 
superpowers 
some allies including west germany and france hoped the united 
states and other industrial democracies would go much further and 
agree at the economic summit in houston to fashion a coordinated 
package of direct assistance to the reeling soviet economy 
bush among others resisted the dispute was blunted for the 
time being when the seven summit partners agreed instead tuesday 
to organize a quick study of the soviet unions needs 
meanwhile the summit leaders gave gorbachev a warm endorsement 
and pledged to help in practical ways those countries that choose 
freedom 
the final communique issued at the close of the summit today 
said prospects for fundamental and longterm economic aid could 
improve if the soviet union comes to a substantial change in 
resources from military to civilian production and ends the 
support to those states which create regional conflict 
the western leaders called for group of international financial 
institutions under international monetary fund supervision to 
conduct the soviet study and complete it by years end but the 
world bank part of that group immediately pronounced the deadline 
unrealistic saying a study of this nature would take a long time 
a year or so 
in the interim for the united states to extend even technical 
assistance is a gesture that is downright revolutionary when 
measured by the standards of just 8 years ago 
after the polish governments crackdown with soviet 
acquiescence on the solidarity labor union in december 1981 the 
western allies were debating how severely to punish the soviets 
economically now the debate is focused on how much the kremlin 
should be rewarded for its change of heart under mikhail 
gorbachevs stewardship 
bush and gorbachev set in motion the concept of us technical 
assistance at the malta summit seven months ago officials now say 
an acceleration of that cooperation may be possible 
technical assistance can cover a variety of different endeavors 
in panama it means helping the government form a new police force 
in nicaragua us experts are helping to implement the 
governments economic policy in el salvador american advisers are 
trying to upgrade the countrys woefully deficient judicial system 
the us position on the soviet union is that direct aid would 
merely be wasted by a system plagued by gross inefficiencies baker 
said on tuesday the biggest favor the west could do for the soviets 
would be to offer its advice to help gorbachev achiev his goal of 
streamlining the soviet economy a number of private experts agree 
with that approach 
some ideas which are at various stages of discussion include 
helping the soviets devise a consumer price index and a stock 
market in a transition to a market economy 
leon aron of the heritage foundation a conservative research 
group said the united states is uniquely positioned among the 
allies to offer advice on these areas to a country as large as the 
soviet union because of the scale of the us economy 
aron rejected the suggestion of some european nations that 
direct financial aid to the soviet union is feasible he said that 
because of systemic inefficiencies there is 8 billion worth of 
imported equipment languishing unopened in soviet ports 
a blank check is wasted he said 
ed a hewitt of the brookings institution said us experts 
could aid the soviets in overcoming such problems as getting food 
to the market place about a third of all soviet food rots before 
reaching the dinner table because of inadequate transportation or 
storage facilities he said 
both hewitt and richard feinberg executive vice president of 
the overseas development council strongly support a major role for 
the world bank and international monetary fund in helping the 
soviets 
financial stabilization and structural changes are sorely needed 
in the soviet union and are precisely the areas the bank and the 
fund have been set up to deal with feinberg said 
the imf makes loans to developing countries providing they agree 
to undertake measures that it believes are necessary to put them on 
a sounder economic footing 
feinberg says that among the imfs success stories are turkey 
mexico bolivia and chile critics argue that imf policies have 
impoverished some countries 
the soviets are not now in a position to benefit from the fund 
or the bank because they are not members of either institution but 
they have indicated a desire to join and the bush administration 
reportedly is weighing options on the subject 
there are other ways the united states could help the soviets 
short of direct assistance 
as an example if the kremlins drop barriers to emigration the 
united states could waive the socalled jacksonvanik amendment 
thereby permitting normal trade between the two countries 
that step in turn could be followed by us trade credits and 
the easing of high technology exports the soviets may act on the 
emigration question in september 
will direct us aid ever be in the cards 
i dont think you should ever say never baker said tuesday 
things can change 
</TEXT>
