<TEXT>
teetering trade barriers in the west and the 
opening of closed economies in the east have been making europe as 
a whole the target of us automakers which are moving with 
unaccustomed speed to exploit the market 
general motors corp ford motor co and to a lesser extent 
chrysler corp have engaged in business in europe for years 
but more recently they quickly have been setting up joint 
manufacturing and supply ventures establishing marketing 
associations and buying all or parts of european automakers as the 
continent begins to emerge as the worlds largest auto market 
trade barriers among the 12member european economic community 
are to be eliminated in 1992 creating an auto market larger than 
north america 
the market would swell further if free trade agreements are 
reached between the dozen ec members and other western and eastern 
european nations 
general motors ford and chrysler each facing weakening 
performances at home increasingly are looking to europe as a 
source of profits and a market for excess us manufacturing 
capacity 
auto analyst david healy of the investment banking firm 
barclays de zoete wedd in new york said tuesday he expected the 
european market to grow to about 13 million cars this year 
generous estimates put the us car market at about 10 million for 
1990 
its something thats a good deal bigger in just passenger 
cars than the united states healy said sales have grown a lot 
over the last few years but have sort of leveled out this year 
theres potential growth in the european minivan and 
sportutility segments 
chrysler which sparked the popularity of minivans in the united 
states has signed an agreement with steyrdaimlerpuch to make 
minivans in austria beginning in spring 1991 executives have said 
the project also may market righthand drive vehicles for the 
united kingdom 
i think there is going to be a scramble to either introduce 
those vans from the united states or companies building them on 
their own healy said this is something coming very rapidly 
historically automakers have wanted to build vehicles where 
they sell them that way they can react quicker to market changes 
avoid import duties and attempt to lessen the stigma of a foreign 
company invading the homeland 
japanese automakers have used the strategy with great success in 
the united states where they faced pressure to restrict imports 
seven japanese companies now operate us transplants with 
honda motor co ltd having opened the first in november 1982 in 
marysville ohio 
the big three have a much older history in europe ford opened a 
british assembly plant in 1911 three years after establishing a 
sales branch in france and the same year gm set up an exporting 
company 
since then ford and gm have grown substantially in europe each 
now has sales or manufacturing operations in more than a dozen 
western european nations chrysler has had a small sales presence 
on the continent 
in 1988 the latest figures available from the motor vehicle 
manufacturers association about 37 percent of fords worldwide 
production came from its european operations and 25 percent of gms 
came from the region 
recent moves have stepped up the pace of european operations 
gm acquired half of swedens saab automobile ab signed an 
agreement to begin making cars in east germany later this year and 
agreed to a 150 million investment in a hungarian vehicle making 
plant 
ford spent 25 billion to acquire the british 
luxuryperformance car maker jaguar plc and has announced that it 
is involved in negotiations focusing on heavy truck and farm 
implement manufacturing with the huge italian company fiat group 
also gm and the soviet automaker volga auto works have signed a 
1 billion deal under which gm will supply pollution and engine 
control systems to the soviet company 
it does provide a very good foundation from which to start to 
learn how to do business learn how to find hotel rooms and make 
telephone calls william hoglund gms executive vice president 
said last month in announcing the deal 
sixteen months ago ford left a consortium of companies looking 
into joint ventures with soviet businesses and is not involved in 
any discussions in that nation now 
at the time of its withdrawal ford said a primary problem was 
finding a way to convert profits paid in soviet rubles into 
currency traded in international markets 
convertibility problems also faced us companies interested in 
moving into east germany but the recent unification of the west 
and east german marks eliminated that hurdle 
in march gm signed an agreement to begin making cars this 
october in east germany for the east german market about 10000 
cars will be made this year and production will increase to about 
150000 annually by the mid1990s 
thats a modest production by us standards but is expected to 
help meet the automobile supply problem in east germany where 
citizens sometimes wait more than half a year for delivery 
