<TEXT>
a floor broker accused of trying to manipulate 
silver prices before the world silver market plunge in 1980 agreed 
wednesday to pay 100000 to settle administrative charges by 
federal futures regulators 
the commodity futures trading commission announced it had 
accepted a settlement offer from norton waltuch a former floor 
broker and account executive with the nowdefunct firm of 
conticommodity services inc 
waltuch and eight other individuals and concerns were accused of 
manipulating and attempting to manipulate the price of silver 
futures contracts and silver bullion in 1979 and 1980 
without admitting or denying the allegations first made by the 
cftc in february 1985 waltuch agreed not to violate federal 
futures trading laws and to pay a civil penalty of 100000 
in addition the cftc suspended his floor broker registration 
for six months and ordered him not to trade for his own account on 
the floor of any exchange for six months 
from september 1979 to midjanuary 1980 silver prices rose from 
11 an ounce to an alltime high of 50 an ounce 
but the price then declined and on march 27 1980 the wealthy 
hunt brothers of dallas couldnt meet a call for 100 million in 
silver futures contracts and the world market plummeted to below 
11 an ounce 
of the other eight others accused of violations by the cftc 
cases remain pending against only one international metals 
investment co ltd 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

