<TEXT>
a former president of the sunbelt savings 
association has been indicted on bank fraud charges in a 700 
million real estate deal the fbi announced today 
edwin t mcbirney iiis indictment comes one month after the 
indictment of donald r dixon former owner of the collapsed vernon 
savings amp loan association in texas 
mcbirney is one of four highprofile thrift executives who have 
been subpoenaed by the us house banking committee to discuss the 
billiondollar failures of their institutions 
mcbirney acquired sunbelt savings in 1982 with five associates 
the thrift engaged in highrisk loans that were either unsecured or 
inadequately secured by commercial real estate and land according 
to government documents 
mcbirney under pressure from government regulators resigned as 
chairman in 1986 
in august 1988 sunbelt and seven other insolvent thrifts were 
consolidated and managed by the federal savings and loan insurance 
corp 
the government spent at least 25 billion in that bailout it 
was part of the federal home loan bank boards southwest plan to 
consolidate and recapitalize ailing thrifts in the region 
the 17count indictment involves the sale of a 708acre plot of 
land in denton county north of dallas 
the indictment charges that mcbirney promised western savings 
association another dallas thrift a 6 million profit on any 
property western wanted to sell if western would provide 30 
million in funding to close another transaction 
that transaction through sunbelt subsidiary sun cal involved 
approximately 700 million worth of california real estate 
mcbirney who is expected to surrender thursday faces to up 85 
years in jail and a 425 million fine if convicted 
</TEXT>
