<DOCNO> AP900711-0250 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
once it was a dying lumber town in rural 
michigan best known for the 14 bars on muddy main street 
that was the midland of the turn of the century when a 
fledgling chemical company called dow decided to set up shop there 
today the city of 37000 about 100 miles north of detroit 
lives and breathes dow chemical co the company provides jobs 
taxes foundation money and an international ambience shared by few 
other small midwest cities 
but it also spews fumes that smell faintly of solvent and 
discharges treated wastewater into the local river prompting 
warnings that anglers shouldnt eat too many bottom fish 
nonetheless the chemistry between dow and midland seems to 
work in many respects it serves as a modernday model for the 
relationship between a city and a major employer midlanders say 
we would perhaps be nonexistent if dow had not come here and 
established this chemical company assistant city manager david 
wirth said 
dow chemical has grown into michigans fourthlargest 
manufacturer and a global giant since it was founded in 1897 and 
it has taken midland along for the ride 
it all started with herbert henry dow who came to town in 1887 
after getting a chemistry degree at clevelands case institute of 
technology 
major commerce in those days was a fading timber industry that 
had surged as chicago rebuilt after its disastrous fire of 1871 
dow tried something new he began his business by drilling brine 
wells and using electric charges to separate chemicals like 
chlorine bromine and sodium hydroxide still the main ingredient 
in dow oven cleaner 
many of the people who came here with dr dow and supported 
him and started off with him became comfortably well off said 
catherine cummins of the midland historical society instead of 
moving to italy with a big boat or living in new york many of them 
are still in town 
dow with 55500 workers worldwide employs about a quarter of 
midland countys labor force of 35250 
the michigan division of midland serves as a research and 
specialty division producing things like latex and aspirin powder 
items that historically have withstood economic whims 
other michigan cities havent been so fortunate 
take the automaking town of flint about 50 miles south of 
midland during the recession year of 1982 flints unemployment 
rate averaged 211 percent vs 127 percent for midland 
over the past 2 years flints jobless rate has seesawed 
between 82 percent and 185 percent midlands unemployment ranged 
from a high of 85 percent in january 1988 to 44 percent last 
november 
theyre midland residents really sheltered from the cyclical 
sensitivity of the automotive industry said sandra st cyr an 
analyst for the michigan employment security commission 
dow also provides a tax shelter of sorts for midland residents 
by making up a quarter of the citys 13 billion tax base 
midland has at least 10 foundations endowed by dows founders 
that pay for good schools and libraries a busy theatrical and arts 
center and a botanical garden 
the relatively low jobless rate coupled with the abundance of 
educated dow professionals that have become attracted to midlands 
schools and cultural activities has helped keep the citys crime 
rate low some residents contend 
i dont think theres a crack house in town said patrick 
dean a midland police officer since 1963 who once served as acting 
police chief its been six or seven years since we had a 
homicide 
in the fbis uniform crime report for 1988 the most recent one 
released midland tallied 1402 reported crimes half the number of 
several similarsized michigan cities 
despite all that dow contributes there are drawbacks to having 
a giant chemical company in the backyard 
a recent ranking of the nations worst toxic polluters shows dow 
ranked no 29 and third in michigan behind general motors corp and 
ford motor co 
the state first advised against eating fish from the 
tittabawassee river in 1978 after traces of the suspected 
carcinogen dioxin were found in dows discharges greenpeace 
canoeists paddled up the river in 1986 to plug dows outlets in 
protest 
in the late 1960s demonstrators came to dows doors to protest 
its manufacture of napalm jellied gasoline and defoliant agent 
orange used in the vietnam war 
the company has since worked hard to portray a greener cleaner 
image 
to cut dioxin discharges dow installed a powerful wasterecovery 
system it also cooperates with environmental groups and 
financially supports wetland preservation and recycling 
the chemical bite to the air also seems to be growing fainter 
ive lived here all my life and let me tell you you cant 
smell anything now like you could before said dean the midland 
police officer 
the city has been spared serious chemical accidents though 
reminders of what could happen occur from time to time 
chlorine gas escaped a decade ago sending emergency personnel 
scrambling last year three chemical tank cars derailed and 
burned sending billows of toxic smoke over nearby freeland where 
3000 residents were evacuated for a week 
nonetheless midland and its neighbors have also savored the 
international flavor produced by dow 
people are more involved in the world since dow has 
facilities all over the world said gordon britton editor of 
midland daily news 
world cup soccer is a nonevent in many communities said 
frank popoff dows president and chief executive officer but not 
in midland 
people here think that footballs are round with black spots on 
them you should kick them a lot and not these elongated things 
</TEXT>
