<TEXT>
the government is recovering misspent funds 
from the officers and directors of failed savings institutions and 
banks at a rate better than 1 million a day a top regulator said 
wednesday 
l william seidman chairman of the federal deposit insurance 
corp said his agency was investigating whether to file suit 
against the officers of 1300 failed thrifts and banks and has 
already filed suit against officials of 500 institutions 
approximately 100 million was recovered last year and more than 
200 million in the first half of this year he said 
that is in excess of 1 million per day in recoveries in 
1990 he said 
president bushsson neil could be among the defendants in a 
suit he served as a director of silverado banking savings and 
loan association denver which collapsed in december 1988 at an 
estimated cost to taxpayers of 1 billion 
seidman who appeared with administration officials before the 
house judiciary subcommittee on criminal justice declined to 
comment on when a decision would be made on the silverado case 
agency officials have said they are considering a suit to recover 
losses from silverado directors 
administration officials have been increasingly hammered by 
democrats to demonstrate that they are doing enough to prosecute 
fraud and recover sampl losses the sampl problem is emerging as a hot 
issue in this years congressional races 
the recoveries are still dwarfed by the cost of bailing out the 
sampl industry estimated by the congressional general accounting 
office to be as high as 500 billion including interest on bailout 
borrowing 
in other savings and loan developments 
seidman and timothy ryan director of the office of thrift 
supervision both promised to treat neil bushs case no differently 
than any other sampl case before them in houston president bush 
repeated his promise not to interfere with regulators and said he 
has had to calm down his other sons who want to go to the 
barricades on neils behalf 
documents released by the office of thrift supervision show 
that regulators believed neil bush was unqualified and 
untrained for his position as director of silverado certainly 
he had no experience in managing a large corporation especially a 
financial institution with almost 2 billion in assets the 
documents said 
the senate approved a broad crime bill that stiffens prison 
terms for savings and loan fraud and offers rewards to 
whistleblowers for turning in sampl looters 
the former president of one of texas largest collapsed thrifts 
was indicted on fraud charges in connection with a 700 million 
real estate scheme fbi officials in dallas announced the 
indictment against edwin t mcbirney iii former president of 
sunbelt savings association 
the house judiciary panel is considering a package of reforms 
designed to speed the governments antifraud effort it would be 
attached to a house version of the broad crime bill adopted by the 
senate 
it would provide more money to hire investigators and attorneys 
to prosecute fraud prevent people convicted of fraud from evading 
restitution by filing for bankruptcy and allow regulators and 
prosecutors to seek to freeze the assets of those accused of fraud 
even before they are found guilty 
members of the panel sparred with rep peter smith rvt who 
is sponsoring a resolution calling for the appointment of a special 
prosecutor to investigate the sampl scandal 
rep john bryant dtexas called the suggestion 
mccarthyism he said the appointment of an independent 
prosecutor is appropriate only when allegations have been leveled 
at high officials who cannot be prosecuted without conflict by the 
attorney general 
smith acknowledged he had no reason to suspect anyone in 
particular but said the standard method of government prosecution 
was not working 
james g richmond the justice departments newly appointed 
special counsel for financial institutions said the department had 
no position on the resolution 
rep charles schumer dny chairman of the subcommittee 
acknowledged the sampl issue had become politicized but he said 
if the flames of partisan passions lit a fire under the 
administration to prosecute sampl thieves so be it 
said richmond we are acutely aware that the american people 
want the savings and loan wrongdoers swiftly and appropriately 
punished we do too 
seidman said fraud has been discovered in about half of the 460 
sampls seized by the government since february 1989 in 40 percent of 
the institutions fraud contributed significantly to a thrift 
failure he said 
many were owned or dominated by one individual and operated 
more like real estate development organizations investment banks 
or mutual funds than thrift institutions he said this 
situation allows for abuse and lack of control 
