<TEXT>
the united states found lastminute common ground 
with its summit partners wednesday on a contentious farm subsidies 
dispute hoping to give a push to longrunning efforts to overhaul 
the world trading system 
the compromise allowed president bush to claim success on his 
top summit priority progress toward eliminating the subsidies that 
he says skew world trade as well as costing taxpayers and consumers 
billions of dollars in government spending and higher food prices 
however the european community americas chief antagonist on 
the issue claimed victory as well leaving the ultimate outcome of 
separate fouryearold international trade negotiations still very 
much in doubt 
even if the united states does persuade european governments to 
lower their farm payments bush would still have to take on 
wellentrenched farm interests to dismantle the us farm support 
program 
bush told reporters at a news conference that he was committed 
to push congress for reductions in us subsidies saying we 
have to do it it is a twoway street with other nations 
rep kika de la garza dtexas chairman of the house 
agriculture committee called the summit agreement encouraging 
but said it will not alter plans to maintain us agriculture 
subsidies as part of a fiveyear farm bill now before congress 
i hasten to point out that while the seven nations represented 
in houston play an important part in world trade any final 
agreement must be reached in geneva with the participation of all 
96 gatt signatory nations de la garza said 
if concrete agreements are reached in geneva then we will 
consider what changes may be necessary in our national agriculture 
policy he said 
administration officials saw the summit agreement as a european 
commitment to significant acrosstheboard reductions in all types 
of farm subsidies officials of the european community interpreted 
the final document as more general than that 
commenting on the disparity of views canadian prime minister 
brian mulroney said that it pointed to a long hard bargaining 
process ahead 
im not under any illusions that well be dealing with a new 
era by christmas or even by next spring he said 
but british prime minister margaret thatcher was more upbeat 
saying she believed the trade outcome would map a new route to 
prosperity 
coming after last weeks very successful nato summit which 
took a major stride towards a more peaceful world the results of 
the meeting in houston are an important step towards a more 
prosperous world for everyone mrs thatcher said 
a senior us official briefing reporters on condition that she 
not be named said that the summit communique represented 
significant progress just in getting the european community back to 
the bargaining table 
now we have a framework within which to negotiate we are 
still very far apart in many areas but we have a framework she 
said 
the united states has been pushing since the venice economic 
summit in 1987 for a commitment to halt a global farm subsidy war 
it estimates is costing 245 billion annually 
but the european community has resisted bushs demand saying it 
would result in the loss of 3 million farmers jobs 
bush officials fear that unless the farm dispute is resolved it 
will kill all chances for successfully completing ambitious global 
trade talks known as the uruguay round 
the administration is counting on those talks to lower a wide 
range of trade barriers and greatly expand opportunities for 
american farmers and businesses believing this will help americas 
100billionplus trade deficits 
the talks known as the uruguay round for the country where they 
began in 1986 face a marathon july 23 negotiating session in 
geneva to draft framework agreements in 15 separate areas 
including agriculture 
those agreements will then be used over the next five months to 
achieve a final agreement by a december deadline for ending the 
discussions 
the economic summit involved discussions among bush and the 
leaders of japan west germany france britain canada and italy 
in their final communique the leaders declared that successful 
completion of the uruguay round was the highest priority on the 
international economic agenda and stressed our determination to 
take the difficult political decisions necessary to achieve 
farreaching substantial results in all areas of the uruguay round 
by the end of this year 
bush told reporters at a news conference wrapping up the 
threeday summit that the leaders had committed at the end of the 
lengthy debate on farm subsidies to maintain our personal 
involvement and to exercise political leadership at every step 
along the way 
the final language in the communique urged each nation to make 
substantial progressive reductions in the areas of export 
subsidies internal price supports and barriers to imports the 
three areas targeted by the united states 
the europeans had opposed singling out specific areas for 
subsidy cuts offering instead to consider all subsidies in an 
aggregate total and then reduce that total 
while us negotiators contended that the compromise reached in 
houston would prohibit that the european community disagreed 
they contended the final communique committed them only to 
reducing the total amount of government subsidies marking no 
change from their original position 
the communique language was sufficiently vague on this point 
that both sides could point to it to support their stands 
bush spoke forcefully on the subject during the summit meetings 
but he faced strong resistance from european countries the leaders 
had to extend their afternoon session tuesday for an extra 90 
minutes grappling with the farm question 
they then dispatched lower level negotiators to work through the 
night to come up with the final language 
the uruguay round is being held under the auspices of the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade a forum and agreement for 
promoting freer trade 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

