<TEXT>
about 300 teamsters union members rallied outside 
pan am offices wednesday to protest what they claim is an 
inadequate contract offer by the airline 
as employees left work throughout the afternoon pan am 
management locked the doors behind them the rally took place at 
the airlines offices near miami international airport 
were legal to strike said joyce hardy business 
representative of the teamsters local 769 but we dont want to 
be another eastern 
eastern airlines has struggled to regain passengers since a 
strike by machinists in march 1989 that helped push the airline 
into bankruptcy court machinists continued picketing wednesday 
down the street from the pan am demonstration 
the teamsters representing reservations ticket computer and 
cargo agents have been working under companyimposed conditions 
for two years since federal mediation failed 
union members have been working without a contract since feb 
21 1988 
were making our statement that were unhappy said connie 
bach a reservations agent at pan am for 17 years 
members criticized the companys offer of a 4 percent wage 
increase ms hardy said union members agreed to 250 million in 
concessions two years ago including an 8 percent salary giveback 
union members said they have not had a raise since 1979 they 
also have complained of having no sick days vacation days or a 
pension plan 
pan am spokeswoman elizabeth hlinko in new york said the 
teamsters were negotiating with the company we do have a 
proposal on the table that offers employees a significant 
improvement over their imposed contract and were hopeful that a 
settlement will be reached soon she said 
