<TEXT>
the chicago mercantile exchange on wednesday 
suspended two traders convicted by a federal jury this week of 
trading violations in the swiss franc futures pit 
the exchanges board of governors charged robert d mosky and 
danny l scheck with violating merc rules that could result in 
expulsions and 275000 in fines exchange spokesman andrew yemma 
said 
the two were accused of committing an act which is 
substantially detrimental to the interest or welfare of the 
exchange and conduct which has a manifest tendency to impair 
the dignity or good name of the exchange a hearing is to 
conducted by the exchange board at a date to be set later pending 
the hearing mosky and scheck have been prohibited from conducting 
customer business at the exchange yemma said in a statement 
a federal jury on monday convicted mosky a floor broker of 
seven felony counts and scheck an independent trader of one 
count stemming from an fbi sting operation at the exchange 
but jurors were unable to reach verdicts on 86 counts against 
the two and a third defendant independent trader david zatz 
prosecutors said they plan to refile the charges 
